# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: endangered-wolf-center
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The **African wild dog** (***Lycaon pictus***), also called **painted dog** and **Cape hunting dog**, is a wild canine native to sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It is the largest wild canine in Africa and the only extant member of the genus *Lycaon*, which is distinguished from *Canis* by dentition highly specialised for a hypercarnivorous diet and by a lack of dewclaws.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] An estimated 6,600 adults (including 1,400 mature individuals) live in 39 subpopulations, all threatened by habitat fragmentation, human persecution, and outbreaks of disease.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] As the largest subpopulation probably consists of fewer than 250 individuals, the African wild dog has been listed as endangered on the IUCN Red List since 1990.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog is a specialized hunter of terrestrial ungulates, mostly hunting at dawn and dusk, but it also displays diurnal activity.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It captures its prey by using stamina and cooperative hunting to exhaust them.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Its natural competitors are lions and spotted hyenas; the former kill the dogs where possible, whilst the latter are frequent kleptoparasites.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Like other canids, the African wild dog regurgitates food for its young, but also extends this action to adults as a central part of the pack's social unit.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The young have the privilege of feeding first on carcasses.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog has been revered in several hunter-gatherer societies, particularly those of the San people and prehistoric Egypt.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The English language has several names for the African wild dog, including African hunting dog, Cape hunting dog, painted hunting dog, painted dog, painted wolf, and painted lycaon.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The earliest written reference for the species appears to be from Oppian, who wrote of the *thoa*, a hybrid between the wolf and leopard, which resembles the former in shape and the latter in colour.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Solinus's *Collectanea rerum memorabilium* from the third century AD describes a multicoloured, wolf-like animal with a mane native to Ethiopia.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog was scientifically described in 1820 by Coenraad Jacob Temminck after having examined a specimen from the coast of Mozambique, which he named *Hyaena picta*.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It was later recognised as a canid by Joshua Brookes in 1827 and renamed *Lycaon tricolor*.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The root word of *Lycaon* is the Greek λυκαίος (*lykaios*), meaning wolf-like.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The specific epithet *pictus* (Latin for painted), which derived from the original *picta*, was later returned to it, in conformity with the International Rules on Taxonomic Nomenclature.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Simpson placed the African wild dog, the dhole, and the bush dog together in the subfamily Simocyoninae on the basis of all three species having similarly trenchant carnassials.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] This grouping was disputed by Juliet Clutton-Brock, who argued that other than dentition, too many differences exist among the three species to warrant classifying them in a single subfamily.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog possesses the most specialized adaptations among the canids for coat colour and diet and for pursuing its prey through its cursorial (running) ability.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It has a graceful skeleton, and the loss of the first digit on its forefeet increases its stride and speed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] This adaptation allows it to pursue prey across open terrain for long distances.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The teeth are generally carnassial-shaped, and its premolars are the largest relative to body size of any living carnivoran with the exception of the spotted hyena.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] On the lower carnassials (first lower molars), the talonid has evolved to become a cutting blade for flesh slicing, with a reduction or loss of the postcarnassial molars.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] This adaptation also occurs in the two other hypercarnivorous canids – the dhole and the bush dog.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog exhibits some of the most varied coat colours among mammals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Individuals differ in patterns and colours, indicating a diversity of the underlying genes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The purpose of these coat patterns may be an adaptation for communication, concealment, or temperature regulation.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] A 2019 study indicated that the *lycaon* lineage diverged from *Cuon* and *Canis* 1.7 million years ago through this suite of adaptations, and these occurred at the same time as large ungulates (its prey) diversified.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The findings also suggest that the African wild dog is largely isolated from gene transfer with other canid species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The oldest African wild dog fossil dates back to 200,000 years ago and was found in HaYonim Cave, Israel.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The evolution of the African wild dog is poorly understood owing to the scarcity of fossil finds.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Some authors consider the extinct *Canis* subgenus *Xenocyon* as ancestral to both the genus *Lycaon* and the genus *Cuon*, which lived throughout Eurasia and Africa from the Early Pleistocene to the early Middle Pleistocene.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Others propose that *Xenocyon* should be reclassified as *Lycaon*.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The species *Canis* (*Xenocyon*) *falconeri* shared the African wild dog's absent first metacarpal (dewclaw), though its dentition was still relatively unspecialised.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] This connection was rejected by one author because *C*.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] (*X*.) *falconeri*'s lack of the first metacarpal is a poor indication of phylogenetic closeness to the African wild dog, and the dentition was too different to imply ancestry.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Another ancestral candidate is the Plio-Pleistocene *Lycaon sekowei* of South Africa on the basis of distinct accessory cusps on its premolars and anterior accessory cuspids on its lower premolars.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] These adaptions are found only in *Lycaon* among living canids, which shows the same adaptations to a hypercarnivorous diet.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] *L. sekowei* had not yet lost the first metacarpal absent in *L. pictus* and was more robust than the modern species, having 10% larger teeth.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog has 78 chromosomes, the same number as those of species in the genus *Canis*.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] In 2018 whole genome sequencing was used to compare the dhole (*Cuon alpinus*) with the African wild dog.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Strong evidence was found of ancient genetic admixture between the two species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Today, their ranges are remote from each other, but during the Pleistocene era, the dhole could be found as far west as Europe.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The study proposes that the dhole's distribution may have once included the Middle East, from where it may have admixed with the African wild dog in North Africa.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] However, no evidence has been found of the dhole having existed in the Middle East or North Africa.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Although the species is genetically diverse, these subspecific designations are not universally accepted.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] East African and Southern African wild dog populations were once thought to be genetically distinct, based on a small number of samples.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] More recent studies with a larger number of samples showed that extensive intermixing has occurred between East African and Southern African populations in the past.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Some unique nuclear and mitochondrial alleles are found in Southern African and northeastern African populations, with a transition zone encompassing Botswana, Zimbabwe, and southeastern Tanzania between the two.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The West African wild dog population may possess a unique haplotype, thus possibly constituting a truly distinct subspecies.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The original Serengeti and Maasai Mara population of painted dogs is known to have possessed a unique genotype, but these genotypes may be extinct.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog is the bulkiest and most solidly built of African canids.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The species stands 60 to 75 cm (24 to 30 in) at the shoulders, measures 71 to 112 cm (28 to 44 in) in head-and-body length, and has a tail length of 29 to 41 cm (11 to 16 in).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Adults have a weight range of 18 to 36 kg (40 to 79 lb).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Typically, dogs from East Africa weigh around 20–25 kg (44–55 lb).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] By body mass, they are only outsized amongst other extant canids by the wolf species complex.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Females are usually 3–7% smaller than males.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Compared to members of the genus *Canis*, the African wild dog is comparatively lean and tall, with outsized ears and lacking dewclaws.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The middle two toepads are usually fused.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Its dentition differs from that of *Canis* by the degeneration of the last lower molar, the narrowness of the canines, and proportionately large premolars, which are the largest relative to body size of any carnivore other than hyenas.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The heel of the lower carnassial M1 is crested with a single, blade-like cusp, which enhances the shearing capacity of the teeth, thus the speed at which prey can be consumed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] This feature, termed "trenchant heel", is shared with two other canids, the Asian dhole and the South American bush dog.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The skull is relatively shorter and broader than those of other canids.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The fur of the African wild dog differs significantly from that of other canids, consisting entirely of stiff bristle-hairs with no underfur.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Colour variation is extreme, and may serve in visual identification, as African wild dogs can recognise each other at distances of 50–100 m (160–330 ft).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Some geographic variation is seen in coat colour, with northeastern African specimens tending to be predominantly black with small white and yellow patches, while southern African ones are more brightly coloured, sporting a mix of brown, black, and white coats.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Much of the species' coat patterning occurs on the trunk and legs.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Little variation in facial markings occurs, with the muzzle being black, gradually shading into brown on the cheeks and forehead.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] A black line extends up the forehead, turning blackish-brown on the back of the ears.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] A few specimens sport a brown, teardrop-shaped mark below the eyes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The back of the head and neck are either brown or yellow.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] A white patch occasionally occurs behind the fore legs, with some specimens having completely white fore legs, chests, and throats.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The tail is usually white at the tip, black in the middle, and brown at the base.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Some specimens lack the white tip entirely or may have black fur below the white tip.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] These coat patterns can be asymmetrical, with each side of the body often having different markings from the other.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog occurs foremost in Southern and East Africa.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It is rare in North Africa and mostly absent in West Africa, with the only potentially viable population occurring in Senegal's Niokolo-Koba National Park.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It is occasionally sighted in other parts of Senegal, Guinea, and Mali.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Its distribution is patchy in East Africa.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It inhabits mostly savannas and arid zones, generally avoiding forested areas.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] This preference is likely linked to its hunting habits, which require open areas that do not obstruct vision or impede pursuit.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It travels through scrubland, woodland, and montane areas in pursuit of prey.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] A forest-dwelling population has been identified in the Harenna Forest, a wet montane forest up to an elevation of 2,400 m (7,900 ft) in the Bale Mountains of Ethiopia.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] At least one record exists of a pack being sighted on the summit of Mount Kilimanjaro.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] In Zimbabwe, it has been recorded at the elevation of 1,800 m (5,900 ft).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] In Ethiopia, several packs were sighted at elevations of 1,900 to 2,800 m (6,200 to 9,200 ft), and a dead individual was found in June 1995 at 4,050 m (13,290 ft) on the Sanetti Plateau.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] A stable population comprising more than 370 individuals is present in Kruger National Park.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog have strong social bonds, stronger than those of sympatric lions and spotted hyenas; thus, solitary living and hunting are extremely rare in the species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It lives in permanent packs consisting of two to 27 adults and yearling pups.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The typical pack size in the Kruger National Park and the Maasai Mara is four or five adults, while packs in Moremi and Selous Game Reserves contain eight or nine.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] However, larger packs have been observed and temporary aggregations of hundreds of individuals may have gathered in response to the seasonal migration of vast springbok herds in Southern Africa.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Males and females have separate dominance hierarchies, with the latter usually being led by the oldest female.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Males may be led by the oldest male, but these can be supplanted by younger specimens; thus, some packs may contain elderly male former pack leaders.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The dominant pair typically monopolises breeding.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The species differs from most other social carnivorans in that males remain in the natal pack, while females disperse (a pattern also found in primates such as gorillas, chimpanzees, and red colobuses).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Furthermore, males in any given pack tend to outnumber females 3:1.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Dispersing females join other packs and evict some of the resident females related to the other pack members, thus preventing inbreeding and allowing the evicted individuals to find new packs of their own and breed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Males rarely disperse, and when they do, they are invariably rejected by other packs already containing males.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Although arguably the most social canid, the species lacks the elaborate facial expressions and body language found in the wolf, likely because of the African wild dog's less hierarchical social structure.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Furthermore, while elaborate facial expressions are important for wolves in re-establishing bonds after long periods of separation from their family groups, they are not as necessary to African wild dogs, which remain together for much longer periods.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The species does have an extensive vocal repertoire consisting of twittering, whining, yelping, squealing, whispering, barking, growling, gurling, rumbling, moaning and hooing.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] African wild dog populations in East Africa appear to have no fixed breeding season, whereas those in Southern Africa usually breed during the April–July period.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] During estrus, the female is closely accompanied by a single male, which keeps other members of the same sex at bay.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The estrus period can last as long as 20 days.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The copulatory tie characteristic of mating in most canids has been reported to be absent or very brief (less than one minute) in African wild dog, possibly an adaptation to the prevalence of larger predators in its environment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The gestation period lasts 69–73 days, with the interval between each pregnancy being 12–14 months typically.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog produces more pups than any other canid, with litters containing around six to 16 pups, with an average of 10, thus indicating that a single female can produce enough young to form a new pack every year.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Because the amount of food necessary to feed more than two litters would be impossible to acquire by the average pack, breeding is strictly limited to the dominant female, which may kill the pups of subordinates.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] After giving birth, the mother stays close to the pups in the den, while the rest of the pack hunts.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] She typically drives away pack members approaching the pups until the latter are old enough to eat solid food at three to four weeks of age.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The pups leave the den around the age of three weeks and are suckled outside.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The pups are weaned at the age of five weeks, when they are fed regurgitated meat by the other pack members.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] By seven weeks, the pups begin to take on an adult appearance, with noticeable lengthening in the legs, muzzle, and ears.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Once the pups reach the age of eight to 10 weeks, the pack abandons the den and the young follow the adults during hunts.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The youngest pack members are permitted to eat first on kills, a privilege which ends once they become yearlings.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] African wild dogs have an average lifespan of about 10 to 11 years in the wild.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] When separated from the pack, an African wild dog becomes depressed and can die as a result of broken heart syndrome.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Packs of African wild dogs have a high ratio of males to females.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] This is a consequence of the males mostly staying with the pack whilst female offspring disperse and is supported by a changing sex-ratio in consecutive litters.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Those born to maiden females contain a higher proportion of males, second litters are half and half and subsequent litters biased towards females with this trend increasing as females get older.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] As a result, the earlier litters provide stable hunters whilst the higher ratio of dispersals amongst the females stops a pack from getting too big.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Populations in the Okavango Delta have been observed 'rallying' before setting out to hunt.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Not every rally results in a departure, but departure becomes more likely when more individual dogs 'sneeze'.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] These sneezes are characterized by a short, sharp exhale through the nostrils.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] When members of dominant mating pairs sneeze first, the group is much more likely to depart.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] If a dominant dog initiates, around three sneezes guarantee departure.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] When less dominant dogs sneeze first, if enough others also sneeze (about 10), then the group will go hunting.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Researchers assert that wild dogs in Botswana "use a specific vocalization (the sneeze) along with a variable quorum response mechanism in the decision-making process [to go hunting at a particular moment]".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Because the African wild dog largely exists in fragmented, small populations, its existence is endangered.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Inbreeding avoidance by mate selection is a characteristic of the species and has important potential consequences for population persistence.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Inbreeding may have been selected against evolutionarily because it leads to the expression of recessive deleterious alleles.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Computer simulations indicate that all populations continuing to avoid incestuous mating will become extinct within 100 years due to the unavailability of unrelated mates.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Thus, the impact of reduced numbers of suitable unrelated mates will likely have a severe demographic impact on the future viability of small wild dog populations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog is a specialised pack hunter of common medium-sized antelopes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It is a primarily diurnal predator and hunts by approaching prey silently, then chasing it in a pursuit clocking at up to 66 km/h (41 mph) for 10–60 minutes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The average chase covers some 2 km (1.2 mi), during which the prey animal, if large, is repeatedly bitten on the legs, belly, and rump until it stops running, while smaller prey is simply pulled down and torn apart.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] African wild dogs adjust their hunting strategy to the particular prey species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] They will rush at wildebeest to panic the herd and isolate a vulnerable individual, but pursue territorial antelope species (which defend themselves by running in wide circles) by cutting across the arc to foil their escape.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Medium-sized prey is often killed in 2–5 minutes, whereas larger prey such as wildebeest may take half an hour to pull down.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Male wild dogs usually perform the task of grabbing dangerous prey, such as warthogs, by the nose.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] A species-wide study showed that by preference, where available, five prey species were the most regularly selected, namely the greater kudu, Thomson's gazelle, impala, Cape bushbuck and blue wildebeest.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] More specifically, in East Africa, its most common prey is the Thomson's gazelle, while in Central and Southern Africa, it targets impala, reedbuck, kob, lechwe and springbok, and smaller prey such as common duiker, dik-dik, hares, spring hares, insects and cane rats.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Staple prey sizes are usually between 15 and 200 kg (33 and 441 lb), though some local studies put upper prey sizes as variously 90 to 135 kg (198 to 298 lb).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] In the case of larger species such as kudu and wildebeest, calves are largely but not exclusively targeted.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] However, certain packs in the Serengeti specialized in hunting adult plains zebras weighing up to 240 kg (530 lb) quite frequently.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Another study claimed that some prey taken by wild dogs could weigh up to 289 kg (637 lb).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] This includes African buffalo juveniles during the dry season when herds are small and calves less protected.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Footage from Lower Zambezi National Park taken in 2021 showed a large pack of African wild dogs hunting an adult, healthy buffalo, though this is apparently extremely rare.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] One pack was recorded to occasionally prey on bat-eared foxes, rolling on the carcasses before eating them.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] African wild dogs rarely scavenge, but have on occasion been observed to appropriate carcasses from spotted hyenas, leopards, cheetahs, lions, and animals caught in snares.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Hunting success varies with prey type, vegetation cover and pack size, but African wild dogs tend to be very successful: often more than 60% of their chases end in a kill, sometimes up to 90%.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] An analysis of 1,119 chases by a pack of six Okavango wild dogs showed that most were short distance uncoordinated chases, and the *individual* kill rate was only 15.5 percent.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Because kills are shared, each dog enjoyed an efficient benefit–cost ratio.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Small prey such as rodents, hares and birds are hunted singly, with dangerous prey such as cane rats and Old World porcupines being killed with a quick and well-placed bite to avoid injury.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Small prey is eaten entirely, while large animals are stripped of their meat and organs, leaving the skin, head, and skeleton intact.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog is a fast eater, with a pack being able to consume a Thomson's gazelle in 15 minutes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] In the wild, the species' consumption is 1.2–5.9 kg (2.6–13.0 lb) per African wild dog a day, with one pack of 17–43 individuals in East Africa having been recorded to kill three animals per day on average.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Unlike most social predators, African wild dogs will regurgitate food for other adults as well as young family members.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Pups old enough to eat solid food are given first priority at kills, eating even before the dominant pair; subordinate adult dogs help feed and protect the pups.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It has been found that African wild dogs packs in the Okavango Delta feed on jackalberry fruits just before going out on the hunt; older individuals consume more fruit than others, and this is probably a learned behaviour, explaining why it has not been found in wild dogs elsewhere.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Lions dominate African wild dogs and are a major source of mortality for both adults and pups.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Population densities are usually low in areas where lions are more abundant.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] One pack reintroduced into Etosha National Park was wiped out by lions.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] A population crash in lions in the Ngorongoro Conservation Area during the 1960s resulted in an increase in African wild dog sightings, only for their numbers to decline once the lions recovered.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] As with other large predators killed by lion prides, the dogs are usually killed and left uneaten by the lions, indicating the competitive rather than predatory nature of the lions' dominance.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] However, a few cases have been reported of old and wounded lions falling prey to African wild dogs.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] On occasion, packs of wild dogs have been observed defending pack members attacked by single lions, sometimes successfully.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] One pack in the Okavango in March 2016 was photographed by safari guides waging "an incredible fight" against a lioness that attacked a subadult dog at an impala kill, which forced the lioness to retreat, although the subadult dog died.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] A pack of four wild dogs was observed furiously defending an old adult male dog from a male lion that attacked it at a kill; the dog survived and rejoined the pack.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] African wild dogs commonly lose their kills to larger predators.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Spotted hyenas are important kleptoparasites and follow packs of African wild dogs to appropriate their kills.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] They typically inspect areas where wild dogs have rested and eat any food remains they find.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] When approaching wild dogs at a kill, solitary hyenas approach cautiously and attempt to take off with a piece of meat unnoticed, though they may be mobbed in the attempt.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] When operating in groups, spotted hyenas are more successful in pirating African wild dog kills, though the dogs' greater tendency to assist each other puts them at an advantage against spotted hyenas, which rarely work cooperatively.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Cases of African wild dogs scavenging from spotted hyenas are rare.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Although African wild dog packs can easily repel solitary hyenas, on the whole, the relationship between the two species is a one-sided benefit for the hyenas, with African wild dog densities being negatively correlated with high hyena populations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] In the Selous Game Reserve, it has been reported that African wild dogs lose 2% of their kills to spotted hyenas, less than 1% to lions, and another less than 1% to larger packs of their own species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] It has been estimated that a 25% kill loss rate would require African wild dogs to spend 7.6–12 hours per day hunting to recover the wasted energy, which is unfeasible and makes them extremely vulnerable to kleptoparasitism.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Beyond piracy, cases of interspecific killing of African wild dogs by spotted hyenas are documented.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] African wild dogs are apex predators, only fatally losing contests to larger social carnivores.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] When briefly unprotected, wild dog pups may occasionally be vulnerable to large eagles, such as the martial eagle, when they venture out of their dens.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Surveys in the Central African Republic's Chinko area revealed that the African wild dog population decreased from 160 individuals in 2012 to 26 individuals in 2017.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] At the same time, transhumant pastoralists from the border area with Sudan moved in the area with their livestock.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The non-governmental organization African Wild Dog Conservancy began working in 2003 to conserve the African wild dog in northeastern and coastal Kenya, a convergence zone of two biodiversity hotspots.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] This area largely consists of community lands inhabited by pastoralists.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] With the help of local people, a pilot study was launched confirming the presence of a population of wild dogs largely unknown to conservationists.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Over the next 16 years, local ecological knowledge revealed this area to be a significant refuge for African wild dogs and an important wildlife corridor connecting Kenya's Tsavo National Parks with the Horn of Africa in an increasingly human-dominated landscape.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] This project has been identified as a wild dog conservation priority by the IUCN/SSC Canid Specialist Group.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Depictions of African wild dogs are prominent on cosmetic palettes and other objects from Egypt's predynastic period, likely symbolising order over chaos and the transition between the wild and the domestic dog.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Predynastic hunters may have identified with the African wild dog, as the Hunters Palette shows them wearing the animals' tails on their belts.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] By the dynastic period, African wild dog illustrations became much less represented, and the animal's symbolic role was largely taken over by the African wolf.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] According to Enno Littmann, the people of Ethiopia's Tigray Region believed that injuring a wild dog with a spear would result in the animal dipping its tail in its wounds and flicking the blood at its assailant, causing instant death.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] For this reason, Tigrean shepherds used to repel wild dog attacks with pebbles rather than with edged weapons.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The African wild dog also plays a prominent role in the mythology of Southern Africa's San people.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] In one story, the wild dog is indirectly linked to the origin of death, as the hare is cursed by the moon to be forever hunted by African wild dogs after the hare rebuffs the moon's promise to allow all living things to be reborn after death.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Another story has the god Cagn taking revenge on the other gods by sending a group of men transformed into African wild dogs to attack them, though who won the battle is never revealed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The San of Botswana see the African wild dog as the ultimate hunter and traditionally believe that shamans and medicine men can transform themselves into wild dogs.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Some San hunters will smear African wild dog bodily fluids on their feet before a hunt, believing that doing so will give them the animal's boldness and agility.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Nevertheless, the species does not figure prominently in San rock art, with the only notable example being a frieze in Mount Erongo showing a pack hunting two antelopes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] The Ndebele have a story explaining why the African wild dog hunts in packs: in the beginning, when the first wild dog's wife was sick, the other animals were concerned.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] An impala went to hare, who was a medicine man.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Hare gave Impala a calabash of medicine, warning him not to turn back on the way to Wild Dog's den.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Impala was startled by the scent of a leopard and turned back, spilling the medicine.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] A zebra then went to Hare, who gave him the same medicine along with the same advice.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] On the way, Zebra turned back when he saw a black mamba, thus breaking the gourd.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] A moment later a terrible howling was heard: Wild Dog's wife had died.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] Wild Dog went outside and saw Zebra standing over the broken gourd of medicine, so Wild Dog and his family chased Zebra and tore him to shreds.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/african-painted-dog] To this day, African wild dogs hunt zebras and impalas as revenge for their failure to deliver the medicine that could have saved Wild Dog's wife.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Even though some practices, like animal fighting, are widely acknowledged as cruel, not all people or cultures have the same definition of what constitutes animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Many would claim that docking a piglet's tail without an anesthetic constitutes cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Others would respond that it is a routine technique for meat production to prevent harm later in the pig's life.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Additionally, laws governing animal cruelty vary from country to country.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] For instance, docking a piglet's tail is routine in the US but prohibited in the European Union (EU).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Utilitarian advocates argue from the position of costs and benefits and vary in their conclusions as to the allowable treatment of animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Some utilitarians argue for a weaker approach that is closer to the animal welfare position, whereas others argue for a position that is similar to animal rights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Animal rights theorists criticize these positions, arguing that the words "unnecessary" and "humane" are subject to widely differing interpretations and that animals have basic rights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] They say that most animal use itself is unnecessary and a cause of suffering, so the only way to ensure protection for animals is to end their status as property and to ensure that they are never viewed as a substance or as non-living things.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Throughout history, some individuals, like Leonardo da Vinci for example, who once purchased caged birds in order to set them free, were concerned about cruelty to animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] His notebooks also record his anger with the fact that humans used their dominance to raise animals for slaughter.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] According to contemporary philosopher Nigel Warburton, for most of human history the dominant view has been that animals are there for humans to do with as they see fit.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Sociologist David Nibert emphasizes that the process of domestication dramatically increased the exploitation of animals by humans, particularly in Eurasia, and asserts that this paved the way for the creation of a modern day, capitalist–driven animal–industrial complex.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Several religious traditions have promoted animal welfare as an important or fundamental concept, and encouraged vegetarianism or veganism.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Examples include Buddhism, Jainism, Hinduism (with certain animals being considered sacred), and some forms of Judaism (many Orthodox Jews do not wear leather).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] René Descartes believed that non-humans are automata — complex machines with no soul, mind, or reason.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] In Cartesian dualism, consciousness was unique to human among all other animals and linked to physical matter by divine grace.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] However, close analysis shows that many human features such as complex sign usage, tool use, and self-consciousness can be found in some animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] In 2012, a prominent group of neuroscientists signed the *Cambridge Declaration on Consciousness*.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] It stated that humans are not the only conscious beings, and that many other animals, including all mammals and birds, also possess consciousness, challenging the Cartesian view of animals as mechanical beings.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Charles Darwin, by presenting the theory of evolution, revolutionized the way that humans viewed their relationship with other species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Darwin believed that not only did human beings have a direct kinship with other animals, but the latter had social, mental, and moral lives too.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Modern philosophers and intellectuals, such as Peter Singer and Tom Regan, have argued that animals' ability to feel pain as humans do makes their well-being worthy of equal consideration.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] There are many precursors of this train of thought.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] These arguments have prompted some to suggest that animals' well-being should enter a social welfare function directly, not just indirectly via its effect only on human well-being.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p01] Many countries have now formally recognized animal sentience and animal suffering, and have passed anti-cruelty legislation in response.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Animal cruelty can be broken down into two main categories: active and passive.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Passive cruelty is typified by cases of neglect, in which the cruelty is a lack of action rather than the action itself.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Oftentimes passive animal cruelty is accidental, born of ignorance.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] In many cases of neglect in which an investigator believes that the cruelty occurred out of ignorance, the investigator may attempt to educate the pet owner, then revisit the situation.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] In more severe cases, exigent circumstances may require that the animal be removed for veterinary care.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] There are studies providing evidence of a link between animal cruelty and violence towards humans.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] A 2009 study found that slaughterhouse employment increases total arrest rates, arrests for violent crimes, arrests for rape, and arrests for other sex offenses in comparison with other industries.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] A history of torturing pets and small animals, a behavior known as zoosadism, is considered one of the signs of certain psychopathologies, including antisocial personality disorder, also known as a psychopathic personality disorder.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Acts of intentional animal cruelty or non-accidental injury may be indicators of serious psychological problems.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] According to the American Humane Association, 13% of intentional animal abuse cases involve domestic violence.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] As many as 71% of pet-owning women seeking shelter at safe houses have reported that their partner had threatened and/or hurt or killed one or more of their pets; 32% of these women reported that one or more of their children had also hurt or killed pets.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Battered women report that they are hesitant about leaving their abusers because they fear what will happen to the animals in their absence.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Animal abuse is sometimes used as a form of intimidation in domestic disputes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Cruelty to animals is one of the three components of the Macdonald triad.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] This behavior is considered to be one of the signs of violent antisocial behavior in children and adolescents.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] According to the studies used to form this model, cruelty to animals is a common (but not universal) behavior in children and adolescents who grow up to become serial killers and other violent criminals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] It has also been found that children who are cruel to animals have often witnessed or been victims of abuse themselves.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] In two separate studies cited by the Humane Society of the United States, roughly one-third of families suffering from domestic abuse indicated that at least one child had hurt or killed a pet.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Monkey hate is a form of sadism where humans have a hatred for monkeys and take pleasure in their suffering.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The phenomenon drew public attention after a global monkey torture ring was uncovered by the BBC in 2023.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Animal testing is regulated to varying degrees in different countries.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] In some cases it is strictly controlled while others have more relaxed regulations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] There are ongoing debates about the ethics and necessity of animal testing.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Proponents argue that it has led to significant advancements in medicine and other fields while opponents raise concerns about cruelty towards animals and question its effectiveness and reliability.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Laboratory animal sourcing can and has involved animal cruelty, particularly when animals are obtained through illegal or unethical means, or when regulations are not followed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Even when legal and regulated, the use of animals in research is ethically controversial because it often involves causing harm or death to sentient beings.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The international trade in primates sees 32,000 wild non-human primates (NHPs) trapped and sold on the international market every year.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] They are sold mostly for use in animal testing, but also for food, for exhibition in zoos and circuses, and for private use as companion animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Under all three of the conceptual approaches to animal cruelty discussed above, performing unnecessary experiments or demonstrations upon animals that cause them substantial pain or distress may be viewed as cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Due to changes in ethical standards, this type of cruelty tends to be less common today than it used to be in the past.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] For example, schoolroom demonstrations of oxygen depletion routinely suffocated birds by placing them under a glass cover, and animals were suffocated in the Cave of Dogs to demonstrate the density and toxicity of carbon dioxide to curious travelers on the Grand Tour.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Cattle in religion and mythology are considered sacred in the Indian religions of Hinduism, Jainism and Buddhism, as well as in some Chinese folk religion and in African paganism.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Cattle played other major roles in many religions, including those of ancient Egypt, ancient Greece, ancient Israel, and ancient Rome.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] In some regions, especially most states of India, the slaughter of cattle is prohibited and their meat (beef) may be taboo.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The production of *foie gras* (the liver of a duck or a goose that has been specially fattened) involves the force-feeding of birds with more food than they would eat in the wild, and more than they would voluntarily eat domestically.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The feed, usually corn boiled with fat (to facilitate ingestion), deposits large amounts of fat in the liver, thereby producing the fatty consistency sought by some gastronomes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Pinikpikan is a chicken or duck dish from the mountains of the Cordillera region in the Philippines.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] As a tradition of the indigenous Igorot people, pinikpikan is prepared by beating a live chicken to death with a stick prior to cooking.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The beating bruises the chicken's flesh by bringing blood to its surface, which is said to improve the flavour after cooking.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The act of beating the chicken, while done in preparation of the dish, violates the Philippine Animal Welfare Act 1998.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The Homarus lobster is usually cooked alive.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The Animal Welfare (Sentience) Act 2022 covers all vertebrates and some invertebrates such as octopuses and lobsters.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Bile bears, sometimes called battery bears, are bears kept in captivity to harvest their bile, a digestive fluid produced by the liver and stored in the gallbladder, which is used by some traditional Asian medicine practitioners.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] It is estimated that 12,000 bears are farmed for bile in China, South Korea, Laos, Vietnam, and Myanmar.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Demand for the bile has been found in those nations as well as in some others, such as Malaysia and Japan.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Kopi luwak, also known as civet coffee, is a coffee that consists of partially digested coffee cherries, which have been eaten and defecated by the Asian palm civet (*Paradoxurus hermaphroditus*).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The cherries are fermented as they pass through a civet's intestines, and after being defecated with other fecal matter, they are collected.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Asian palm civets are increasingly caught in the wild and traded for this purpose.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Growing numbers of intensive civet "farms" have been established and are operated in Southeast Asia, confining tens of thousands of animals to live in battery cages and be force-fed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Eating live animals is a practice found in various cultures around the world, often considered a delicacy or traditional food.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] However, this practice may be considered cruel, as eating live animals or parts of live animals can cause significant suffering and distress, and is even unlawful in certain jurisdictions under animal cruelty laws.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Eating live seafood in Japanese cuisine includes practices such as *ikizukuri* (freshly killed and arranged to appear alive), and *odorigui* (seafood eaten while still moving), including *odori ebi* ("dancing shrimp").
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] All are controversial for animal welfare reasons.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] One example of eating live larvae is the witchetty grub of Aboriginal Australian cuisine, which can be eaten alive and raw or cooked.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Primate cognition encompasses a wide range of advanced intellectual and behavioral skills, including problem-solving, tool use, social learning, cooperation, and even cultural transmission.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Monkey meat is the flesh and other edible parts derived from monkeys, a kind of bushmeat.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Human consumption of monkey meat has been historically recorded in numerous parts of the world, including multiple Asian and African nations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Monkey meat consumption has been reported in parts of Europe and the Americas as well.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Monkey brains is a supposed dish consisting of, at least, partially, the brain of some species of monkey or ape.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Dog intelligence is widely recognized, with dogs demonstrating advanced problem-solving, emotional sensitivity, and strong social bonds.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Dog meat consumption, particularly in Vietnam, has been criticized and condemned by many both within the country and internationally, as most of the dogs are pets that were kidnapped and slaughtered in brutal ways, usually by bludgeoning, stabbing, burning alive, or throat-slitting.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Cat intelligence is well-documented, with domestic cats exhibiting complex social behaviors, problem-solving skills, and the ability to form strong bonds with humans.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Cat meat is meat prepared from domestic cats for human consumption.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Some countries serve cat meat as a regular food, whereas others have only consumed some cat meat in desperation during wartime, famine or poverty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] As cat ownership grew in China, opposition to cat meat increased.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] In 2006, activists forced a Shenzhen restaurant to stop selling cat meat, two years after the Chinese Animal Protection Network (CAPN) began organizing protests against dog and cat meat in multiple cities.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] CAPN's efforts helped raise awareness and reduce demand.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] In 2020, Four Paws and Change For Animals urged Vietnam to reinstate bans on the cat meat trade, highlighting ongoing regional concerns.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Bird intelligence is remarkable, with ducks and chickens showing advanced abilities.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Bird brains have two-to-four times the neuron packing density of mammal brains, for higher overall efficiency.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Despite this, both are widely used as food and often face cruel conditions in factory farming, raising serious ethical concerns about animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Additionally, practices such as duck-baiting highlight a long legacy of animal exploitation.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] According to some news reports, buntings were blinded before cooking.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Pig intelligence is among the highest in the mammal world; pigs display a wide range of complex behaviors, like being able to play video games, understanding human instructions and even using tools.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Despite this high level of intelligence and emotional sensitivity, pigs are frequently subjected to animal cruelty—such as being forced to participate in pig wrestling events, confined in cramped factory farms, or neglected—which causes them unnecessary stress, pain, and suffering.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Equine intelligence is increasingly recognized, with recent studies showing that horses possess advanced cognitive abilities such as strategic thinking, problem-solving, and model-based learning—skills once thought to be beyond their capacity.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Horse slaughter is the practice of slaughtering horses to produce meat for consumption.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Humans have long consumed horse meat; the oldest known cave art, the 30,000-year-old paintings in France's Chauvet Cave, depict horses with other wild animals hunted by humans.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Equine domestication is believed to have begun to raise horses for human consumption.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The practice has become controversial in some parts of the world due to several concerns: whether horses are (or can be) managed humanely in industrial slaughter; whether horses not raised for consumption yield safe meat, and whether it is appropriate to consume what some view as a companion animal.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Eating octopus, is considered cruel by many due to cephalopod intelligence, as octopuses demonstrate advanced problem-solving skills and self-awareness.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] There is currently no validated humane method of slaughter for octopuses, as their nervous system isn't centralized.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Ethical concerns arise with eating dolphins because of cetacean intelligence, with dolphins exhibiting complex social behaviors, language comprehension, and a high degree of self-recognition.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Dolphin drive hunting, a practice involving the herding and killing of dolphins, intensifies these ethical issues.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The practice of cruelty to animals for divination purposes is found in ancient cultures , and some modern religions such as Santeria continue to do animal sacrifices for healing and other rituals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Taghairm was performed by ancient Scots to summon devils.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] An investigation by the Animal Welfare Board of India concluded that "*jallikattu* is inherently cruel to animals".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Animal welfare organisations such as the Federation of Indian Animal Protection Organisations (FIAPO) and PETA India have protested against the practice.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The Kambala, Kambla or Kambula is an annual buffalo race held in the southwestern Indian state of Karnataka.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] It is similar to maramadi from Kerala Traditionally, it is sponsored by local Tuluva landlords and households in the coastal districts of Dakshina Kannada, Udupi and Bhatkal of Karnataka and Kasaragod of Kerala, a region collectively known as Tulu Nadu.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Many have criticised Kambala as cruel to the racing buffaloes, which are driven by whips.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Noted animal-rights activist Maneka Gandhi expressed concerns about the ill treatment of buffaloes during the race.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] While Kambala organizers contend that whips are necessary to elicit maximum speed, government officials advise the riders to be gentle on buffaloes and avoid using whips during the race.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Onychectomy, popularly known as declawing, is an operation to remove an animal's claws surgically by means of the amputation of all or part of the distal phalanges, or end bones, of the animal's toes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Declawing of crabs is the process whereby one or both claws of a crab are manually detached before the return of the live crab to the water, as practiced in the fishing industry worldwide.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Crabs commonly have the ability to regenerate lost limbs after a period of time, and thus declawing is viewed as a potentially more sustainable method of fishing.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Due to the time it takes for a crab to regrow lost limbs, however, whether or not the practice represents truly sustainable fishing is still a point of scientific inquiry, and the ethics of declawing are also subject to debates over pain in crustaceans.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Spain has a number of festivals that involve some sort of animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Among them are burning the bull, donkey baiting, shaving of the beasts (Galicia), garrotting the galgos, quail catapulting, Day of the Geese, running of the bulls, and bull fighting.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Bullfighting is criticized by animal rights or animal welfare activists, referring to it as a cruel or barbaric blood sport in which the bull suffers severe stress and slow, torturous death.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Several activist groups undertake anti-bullfighting actions in Spain and other countries.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The "Toro Jubilo" or Toro embolado in Soria, Medinaceli, Spain, is a festival associated with animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] During this festival, balls of pitch are attached to a bull's horns and set on fire.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The bull is then released into the streets and will run around in pain, often smashing into walls in an attempt to douse the fire as spectators attempt to dodge the animal.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The pitch balls can burn for hours, and they burn the bull's horns, body, and eyes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The animal rights group PACMA has described the fiesta as "a clear example of animal mistreatment".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Dog fighting is a sport that turns dogs against one another in a ring or a pit for gambling or the entertainment of the spectators.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Dogs are often bred and selected for gameness, a trait that refers to their willingness to continue fighting despite injury or exhaustion, which further intensifies the cruelty of these events.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Cockfighting is a blood sport involving domesticated roosters as the combatants.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Donkey-baiting is a blood sport involving the baiting of donkeys against dogs.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] An elephant execution, sometimes called **elephant lynching**, is a pseudo-legal or performative public spectacle where a captive elephant is killed in order to punish it for being a "bad elephant" (behaviors that had, threatened, injured, or killed humans).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Ram fighting is a blood sport between two rams (large-horned male sheep), held in a ring or open field.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] It is commonly found in sheep or goat husbandry culture in Africa, Asia and Europe.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] In Nigeria, Uzbekistan and Indonesia, ram fighting gains popularity among locals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Although categorized as a blood sport and an act of animal cruelty, ram fights rarely resulted in the death of the defeated ram, as the loser often is allowed to flee the arena.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The usage of animals in professional wrestling has varied through the profession's history.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Animals that have been used as opponents to humans in matches include pig wrestling, bears, tigers, cheetahs and orangutans.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The use of animals in professional wrestling, particularly in acts such as bear wrestling or involving wild animals as performers, is widely regarded as animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] These practices often subject animals to stressful, unnatural, and dangerous situations, sometimes resulting in injury, neglect, or death.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Historical examples include, chained, declawed and muzzled bears forced to wrestle humans, as well as the use of snakes, tigers, and other wild animals in matches or as props.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Such uses have been criticized for exploiting animals for entertainment, and bear wrestling is now illegal in many jurisdictions.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Chilean rodeo is generally considered more cruel than common (North American) rodeo by animal welfare organizations and critics, primarily due to differences in how calves are treated and the lack of protective regulations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Animal rights organizations reject calling Chilean rodeo a sport, objecting to the treatment of animals—especially calves, which are repeatedly charged against a wall by horses for points.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] While supporters claim injuries are rare and animals are inspected, activists argue the events cause psychological and physical trauma.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Protests have occurred, with some met by violence, and calls to ban rodeo have grown, similar to movements against bullfighting in Spain.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The largest rattlesnake round-up in the United States is held in Sweetwater, Texas.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Held every year since 1958, the event currently attracts approximately 30,000 visitors per year and in 2006 each annual round-up was said to result in the capture of 1% of the state's rattlesnake population.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Rattlesnake round-ups became a concern by animal welfare groups and conservationists due to claims of animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] In response, some round-ups impose catch-size restrictions or releasing captured snakes back into the wild.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The use of animals in the circus has been controversial since animal welfare groups have documented instances of animal cruelty during the training of performing animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Animal abuse in circuses has been documented such as keeping them in small enclosures, lack of veterinary care, abusive training methods, and lack of oversight by regulating bodies.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Animal trainers have argued that some criticism is not based on fact, including beliefs that shouting makes the animals believe the trainer is going to hurt them, that caging is cruel and common, and that the use of whips, chains or training harms animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Bolivia has enacted what animal rights activists called the world's first ban on all animals in circuses.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Cruelty to animals has often been filmed on video and uploaded to social media websites or private Internet groups.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] This may involve large-scale, systematic operations; a notable example of this was a global monkey torture ring uncovered by the BBC in June 2023, where participants would produce and distribute videos of monkeys being hurt and killed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The video-sharing site YouTube has been criticized for hosting thousands of videos of real-life animal cruelty, especially the feeding of one animal to another for entertainment and spectacle.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Although some of these videos have been flagged as inappropriate by users, YouTube has generally declined to remove them, unlike videos that include copyright infringement.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] In 2021, YouTube banned staged animal rescue videos, where animals were purposely put in danger before being saved.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Animal cruelty has long been an issue in filmmaking industry, with even some big-budget Hollywood films receiving criticism for allegedly harmful—and sometimes lethal—treatment of animals during production.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Court decisions have addressed films that harm animals such as videos that in part depict dog fighting.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Currently, there is no federal or state law specifically governing the use of animals in filmed media, though the federal Animal Welfare Act (AWA) and state cruelty laws indirectly apply.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Luis Buñuel's pseudo-documentary *Land Without Bread* (1933) depicts Spain in the 1930s.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] In one scene, wealthy people shoot a goat (for fun), and in another, they smear honey on a sick donkey so that bees can sting it to death.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] The American Humane Association (AHA) has been associated with monitoring American film-making since the release of the film *Jesse James* (1939), in which a horse was pushed off a plank and drowned in a body of water after having fallen 40 feet into it.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Initially, monitoring of animal cruelty was a partnership between the AHA and the Motion Picture Producers and Distributors of America (also called the Hays office) through the Motion Picture Production Code.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] Provisions in the code discouraged "apparent cruelty to children and animals", and because the Hays Office had the power to enforce this clause, the AHA often had access to sets to assess adherence to it.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p02] However, because the AHA's Hollywood office depended on the Hays Office for the right to monitor sets, the closure of the Hays Office in 1966 corresponded with an increase in animal cruelty on movie sets.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In the famous and now classic science fiction film, *The Incredible Shrinking Man* (1957), a grown man shrinks to a tiny size and fights a house spider.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The film used large live tarantulas (trickily solved by filming the man), 24 of which died during filming due to the intense heat and bright lights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] One of the most infamous examples of animal cruelty in the film was Michael Cimino's flop *Heaven's Gate* (1980), in which numerous animals were brutalized and even killed during production.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Cimino allegedly killed chickens and bled horses from the neck to gather samples of their blood to smear on actors for *Heaven's Gate*, and also allegedly had a horse blown up with dynamite while shooting a battle sequence, the shot of which made it into the film.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] This film played a large part in renewed scrutiny of animal cruelty in films and led to renewed official on-set jurisdiction to monitor the treatment of animals by the AHA in 1980.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In the 1969 film "Fando and Lis", there is a scene where director Jodorowsky slits the throats of live geese.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] After the release of the film *Reds* (1981), the star and director of the picture, Warren Beatty apologized for his Spanish film crew's use of tripwires on horses while filming a battle scene, when Beatty was not present.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Tripwires were used against horses when *Rambo III* (1988) and *The 13th Warrior* (1999) were being filmed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] A water buffalo was sliced nearly in half during the production of *Apocalypse Now* (1979), while a donkey was bled to death for dramatic effect for the Danish film *Manderlay* (2005), in a scene later deleted from the film.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] There is a case of cruelty to animals in the South Korean film *The Isle* (2000), according to its director Kim Ki-Duk.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In the film, a real frog is skinned alive while fish are mutilated.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Seven animals were killed for the camera in the controversial Italian film *Cannibal Holocaust* (1980).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The images in the film include the slow and graphic beheading and ripping apart of a turtle, a monkey being beheaded and its brains being consumed by natives and a spider being chopped apart.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] *Cannibal Holocaust* was only one film in a collective of similarly themed movies (cannibal films) that featured unstaged animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Their influences were rooted in the films of Mondo filmmakers, which sometimes contained similar content.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In several countries, *Cannibal Holocaust* was banned or allowed for release with most of the animal cruelty edited out.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In the Hungarian Judit Elek's film *Memories of a River* (1990), 14 sheep were burned alive.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] A horse was allegedly killed on the set of Andrzej Wajda's film *The Ashes* (1965).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In the film Fort Tilden (2014), the main characters find kittens in a trash can and - although they initially wanted to save them - end up leaving them there.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In *Al sur del edén* (1984), a female character lies on her bed and rubs a live canary against her genitals for sexual gratification.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] (Only the woman's legs are shown from the side, the scene may not be real, and she only holds the bird between her legs.) In the film Malèna (2000), young boys burn ants to death on the beach with torches.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In *Anatomy of Hell* (2004), a little boy throws a live baby bird to the ground.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Slaughterhouse animals being butchered are shown in the 1949 French film *Blood of the Beasts* (pigs) and in the 1963 Hungarian film *Elégia* (horses).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] It is unclear whether a pig is killed in the Hungarian film Taxidermia (2006).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Slaughterhouse scenes as well as the trampling of frogs were shown in the Korean film Mago (2002), and an (allegedly dying) kitten is drowned in the Hungarian film *Hypocritical* (2006).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In the film *The Reflecting Skin* (1990), children torture a frog.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In the film *The Lighthouse* (2019), a seagull opens its beak in a cistern, and then another is beaten to death by a lighthouse keeper who goes mad.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The seagull was not actually killed during filming. „The production team has emphasized that no seagulls were harmed during the filming.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The SAG has contracted with the AHA for monitoring animal use during filming or while on the set.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Compliance with this arrangement is voluntary and only applies to films made in the United States.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Films monitored by the American Humane Association may bear one of their end-credit messages.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Many productions, including those made in the United States, do not advise AHA or SAG of animal use in films, so there is no oversight.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Some other animal welfare organizations worldwide, such as the Animal Anti-Cruelty League in South Africa, have also monitored the use of animals in the film.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The on-set management of animal welfare is often an internal production matter or handled by registered animal handling businesses, rather than a publicly monitored and credited one.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The responsibility ultimately rests with the producer or their representative.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Similarly, animals with very small roles which might not warrant a dedicated, prominent credit in the Japanese system.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The documentaries *Zoo* (2007) and *Donkey Love* (2012) examined serious sexual perversions directed at animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] There is another film, *Equus* (1977), a fictional story that also features cruelty to horses.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Zoos and aquariums can be considered a form of animal cruelty when the conditions of captivity negatively impact the physical and psychological well-being of the animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Roadside zoos are found throughout North America, particularly in remote locations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] They are often small, for-profit zoos, often intended to attract visitors to some other facility, such as a gas station.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The animals may be trained to perform tricks, and visitors are able to get closer to them than in larger zoos.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Since they are sometimes less regulated, roadside zoos are often subject to accusations of neglect and cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Animal welfare activists suggest a total ban on fur production due to the suffering inflicted on animals, especially minks.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] It has been suggested that fur production is immoral as fur clothes are luxury items.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Minks are solitary and territorial animals; however, in fur farms, they are raised in cages and skinned after being killed either by breaking their necks or using lethal gas.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Animal hoarding involves keeping more animals than can be properly cared for, often resulting in neglect and poor living conditions.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Similarly, a puppy mill is a commercial breeding facility where dogs are kept in overcrowded, inhumane conditions for profit, with little regard for their welfare.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Both situations cause significant suffering for the animals involved.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Some animal rights and anti-hunting activists regard hunting as a cruel, perverse and unnecessary blood sport.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Trophy hunting is largely a recreational activity causing death and injury to a significant number of animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In poaching the animal is killed and valuable parts such as tusks or bones are collected.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Canned hunting refers to the practice of bringing exotic animals as trophies to private land for hunting.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Despite being cruel to animals, hunting is practiced in thousands of private properties around the world and is considered a profitable business.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Internet hunting is the practice of hunting via remotely controlled firearms that can be aimed and shot using online webcams.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Internet hunting may be considered cruel because it involves shooting confined animals remotely, which may give them no chance to escape and may cause unnecessary suffering due to poor aim or delayed death.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] This practice may be condemned for treating animals as mere targets rather than respecting their welfare.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Farm animals are generally produced in large, industrial facilities that house thousands of animals at high densities; these are sometimes called factory farms.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Similarly, it has been suggested by campaign groups that chickens, cows, pigs, and other farm animals are among the most numerous animals subjected to cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] For example, because male chickens do not lay eggs, newly hatched males are culled using macerators or grinders.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Worldwide meat overconsumption is another factor that contributes to the miserable situation of farm animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Many undercover investigators have exposed the animal cruelty taking place inside the factory farming industry and there is evidence to show that consumers provided with accurate information about the process of meat production and the abuse that accompanies it has led to changes in their attitudes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The American Veterinary Medical Association accepts maceration subject to certain conditions, but recommends alternative methods of culling as more humane.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Egg-laying hens are then transferred to "battery cages" where they are kept in high densities.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Matheny and Leahy attribute osteoporosis in hens to this caging method.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Broiler chickens suffer similar situations, in which they are fed steroids to grow at a super-fast speed, so fast that their bones, heart, and lungs often cannot keep up.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Broiler chickens under six weeks old suffer painful crippling due to fast growth rates, whilst one in a hundred of these very young birds dies of heart failure.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] To reduce aggression in overcrowded conditions, shortly after birth piglets are castrated, their tails are amputated, and their teeth are clipped, and earmarked.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Calves are sometimes raised in veal crates, which are small stalls that immobilize calves during their growth, reducing costs and preventing muscle development, making the resulting meat a pale color, preferred by consumers.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In the United States, animal cruelty such as soring, which is illegal, sometimes occurs on farms and ranches, as does lawful but cruel treatment such as livestock branding.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Since ag-gag laws prohibit video or photographic documentation of farm activities, these practices have been documented by secret photography taken by whistleblowers or undercover operatives from such organizations as Mercy for Animals and the Humane Society of the United States posing as employees.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Agricultural organizations such as the American Farm Bureau Federation have successfully advocated for laws that tightly restrict secret photography or concealing information from farm employers.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] A downer is an animal, usually livestock, that cannot stand on its own and therefore is to be killed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] A **downed** animal, one that is unable to stand, is not necessarily a downer.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Neglect, abuse, or inhumane handling of downer animals is considered animal cruelty and is illegal in many jurisdictions.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Tail docking in dogs is widely considered animal cruelty when performed for cosmetic or non-medical reasons.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Painting fish using artificial dyes, injections, or caustic dips is considered cruel and unnecessary by animal welfare organizations and experts.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Animal neglect is a form of abuse that involves failing to provide adequate care, nutrition, shelter, or medical attention to animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] A study in Pinhais, Brazil, examined the crime of companion animal neglect within households and found it was more common in homes with a larger number of animals, poor economic conditions, the presence of disabled individuals, and lower educational levels among owners.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Identifying these factors is important for creating strategies to prevent this crime.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Many apartment complexes and rental homes institute no-pet policies.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] No pet policies are a leading cause of animal abandonment, which is considered a crime in many jurisdictions.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In many cases, abandoned pets have to be euthanized due to the strain they put on animal shelters and rescue groups.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Abandoned animals often become feral or contribute to feral populations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In particular, feral dogs can pose a serious threat to pets, children, and livestock.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In Ontario, Canada, no pet policies are outlawed under the Ontario Landlord and Tenant Act and are considered invalid even when a tenant signs a lease that includes a no pets clause.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Similar legislation has also been considered in Manitoba.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Pinioning is the act of surgically removing one pinion joint, the joint of a bird's wing furthest from the body, to prevent flight.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Pinioning is often done to waterfowl and poultry.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] It is not typically done to companion bird species such as parrots.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] This practice is unnecessary and restricted in many countries.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Pinioning is legally restricted in many countries.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In England, if the bird is more than 10 days old, its pinioning may only be performed using anaesthetic and, regardless of the bird's age, the procedure is illegal unless carried out by a veterinarian.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] It is also illegal to perform on farmed birds.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In Austria, pinioning is prohibited based on §5 (Prohibition of cruelty to animals) and §7 (Prohibited interventions performed on animals) of the Animal Protection Act.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Animal sexual abuse, or bestiality, occurs when an individual exploits a non-human animal for their own sexual pleasure or for the pleasure of others.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Bestiality is strongly associated by many with zoophilia, a paraphilia involving sexual attraction to non-human animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] One such individual is Douglas Spink, who was convicted of allegedly owning a bestiality farm in which several animals such as dogs, horses and mice were found.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Horse-ripping, or horse slashing, is an animal cruelty phenomenon involving serious injuries in horses, often involving mutilation of their genitalia and slashing of the flank or neck.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] It has not been established, however, how often these injuries are caused by human cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] "Horse-ripping" is not an entirely neutral term since it implies there is always a human act behind the mutilations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In some cases, traffickers have attached drug packages to animals in an attempt to smuggle contraband.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] This method is more common than surgical implantation, as it is simpler and less risky for traffickers.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In very rare cases, traffickers have surgically implanted drugs into animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] At Miami International Airport in 1993, authorities discovered that some of the 312 boa constrictors in a shipment from Colombia had been surgically filled with condoms containing a total of 80 pounds (36 kg) of cocaine, resulting in the death of all the snakes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Wildlife smuggling often involves transporting live animals in cruel conditions, causing them great suffering.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Animals are frequently confined in cramped spaces without food or water, leading to injury, illness, or death.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] This inhumane treatment makes wildlife smuggling a serious form of animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Despite existing regulations in many countries, transport cruelty remains a widespread problem due to inadequate enforcement and economic pressures to minimize costs.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Animals being moved for slaughter, sale, or display are frequently kept in cramped conditions for extended periods, with minimal attention to their physical and psychological needs.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] This issue is especially pronounced during long-distance transport, such as when animals are shipped from other countries or even across continents.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] During these journeys, animals may endure days or even weeks of travel, often facing extreme temperatures, lack of food and water, and insufficient rest.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The stress and injuries sustained during transport can have lasting effects on animal welfare, and in some cases, animals may not survive the journey.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Addressing transport cruelty—particularly in the context of international and intercontinental movement—requires stricter oversight, better training for handlers, and a commitment to prioritizing animal well-being throughout the entire transportation process.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] One concern about the welfare of horses destined for slaughter is the long distances the horses are sometimes transported to a slaughterhouse.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In 2013, 32,841 horses were slaughtered in Italy; of these, 32,316 were transported from other EU states.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Snares are one of the simplest traps and are very effective.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] They are cheap to produce and easy to set in large numbers.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] A snare traps an animal around the neck or the body; a snare consists of a noose made usually by wire or a strong string.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Snares are widely criticised by animal welfare groups for their cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Domestic animals accidentally captured in glue traps can be released by carefully applying cooking oil or baby oil to the contact areas and gently working until the animal is free.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Many animal rights groups, such as the Humane Society of the United States and In Defense of Animals, oppose the use of glue traps for their cruelty to animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Military animals are creatures that have been employed by humankind for use in warfare.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] They are a specific application of working animals; examples include dogs, dolphins, elephants, and horses.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Only recently has the involvement of animals in war been questioned, and practices such as using animals for fighting, as living bombs , or for military testing purposes (such as during the Bikini Atoll atomic experiments) may now be criticized for being cruel.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Princess Anne, Princess Royal, the patron of the British Animals in War Memorial, stated that animals adapt to what humans want them to do, but that they will not do things that they do not want to, even with training.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Animal participation in the human conflict was commemorated in the United Kingdom in 2004 with the erection of the Animals in War Memorial in Hyde Park, London.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In 2008 a video of a US Marine throwing a puppy over a cliff during the Iraq conflict was popularised as an internet phenomenon and attracted widespread criticism of the soldier's actions for being an act of cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The following are lists of invasive procedures that cause pain, routinely performed on farm animals, and housing conditions that routinely cause animal welfare concerns.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In one survey of United States homeowners, 68% of respondents said they consider the price of meat a more important issue.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] 'Blinders' or 'spectacles' are included as some versions require a pin to pierce the nasal septum.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] 'Dubbing' is the procedure of removing the comb, wattles and sometimes earlobes of poultry.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Removing the wattles is sometimes called "dewattling".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] 'Marking' is the simultaneous mulesing, castration, and tail docking of lambs.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The Southern pig-tailed macaque is the only monkey species widely used for labor, especially in Thailand and Malaysia, where they have been trained for centuries—mainly through punishment-based methods—to harvest coconuts and other fruits.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Although now limited to a small number of farmers, the practice persists, with training schools still operating in southern Thailand and the Malaysian state of Kelantan.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The practice drew international attention in 2019 when PETA exposed the use of macaques for coconut harvesting in Thailand, leading to calls for boycotts of coconut products.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] PETA later clarified that this practice does not occur in other major coconut-producing regions such as the Philippines, India, Brazil, Colombia, or Hawaii.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Bear pits have largely fallen out of favor, as many zoos now try to make their animals' accommodations more natural.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Zoo visitors tend to view animals in natural settings as "active", and those in more artificial settings as "passive".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Bull running was a custom practised in England until the 19th century.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] It involved chasing a bull through the streets of a town until it was weakened, then slaughtering the animal and butchering it for its meat.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Bull running became illegal in 1835, and the last bull run took place in Stamford, Lincolnshire, in 1839.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The practice was not confined to any particular region, with bull runs also documented at Axbridge in the south west, Canterbury and Wokingham in the south east, Tutbury in the midlands, and Wisbech in the east.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Cat burning was a form of cruelty to animals as an entertainment or festivity in Western and Central Europe prior to the 1800s.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] People would gather cats and hoist them onto a bonfire causing death by burning or otherwise through the effects of exposure to extreme heat.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In the medieval to early modern periods, cats, which were associated with vanity and witchcraft, were sometimes burned as symbols of the devil.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The Cave of Dogs (Italian: *Grotta del Cane*) is a cave near Naples, Italy.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Volcanic gases seeping into the cave give the air inside a high concentration of carbon dioxide.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Dogs held inside would faint; at one time this was a tourist attraction.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] A diving horse is an attraction that was popular in North America in the mid-1880s, in which a horse would dive into a pool of water, sometimes from as high as 60 feet.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Dog spinning (Bulgarian: тричане на куче(та), *trichane na kuche(ta)*) is a ritual that was traditionally practiced on the first day of Lent in the village of Brodilovo in southeastern Bulgaria.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The Foreign Cattle Market is a significant historical example of industrial animal handling and slaughter.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] While not intended as animal cruelty, many of its practices would be considered problematic today.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Geek shows were an act in traveling carnivals and circuses of early America and were often part of a larger sideshow.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The billed performer's act consisted of a single geek, who stood in the center ring to chase live chickens.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] It ended with the performer biting the chickens' heads off and swallowing them.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Goat throwing (in Spanish: *Lanzamiento de cabra desde campanario* or *Salto de la cabra*) was a festival celebrated in the town of Manganeses de la Polvorosa, province of Zamora, Spain, on the fourth Sunday of January.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The festival coincided with the commemoration of Saint Vincent the Martyr.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] The act of goldfish swallowing was a fad first popularized by students at American colleges in the late 1930s.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Kots Kaal Pato was an event held annually in the town of Citilcum, located in the municipality of Izamal, within the state of Yucatán, Mexico.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] In it, piñatas stuffed with live animals were broken and ducks were hung from a wooden structure to later behead them.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p03] Since 2016, as a result of the efforts of Humane Society International Mexico and local organizations, the event no longer has this type of practices, instead featuring various sports and cultural activities.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Many jurisdictions around the world have enacted statutes that forbid cruelty to some animals but these vary by country and in some cases by the use or practice.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Egyptian law states that anyone who inhumanely beats or intentionally kills any domesticated animal may be jailed or fined.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Egyptian Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals was established over a hundred years ago and was instrumental in promoting a 1997 ban on bullfighting in Egypt.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In ancient Egyptian law, the killers of cats or dogs were executed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Animal cruelty in Nigeria is prohibited under Section 495 of the Criminal Code (1990).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] These include, according to 495(1)(a), cruelly beating, kicking, over-loading, infuriating, or terrifying an animal, or allowing this to happen as the owner.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Section 495(1)(b) defines failure to act as the willful or unreasonable doing or omission of any act that causes unnecessary suffering (or as the owner, permitting an act that causes unnecessary suffering).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] This section also prohibits transporting animals in a way that causes unnecessary suffering (c), administering poison (d), performing operations without due care (e), and actions related to animal fighting (f).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Act contains a detailed list of prohibited acts of cruelty including overloading, causing unnecessary suffering due to confinement, chaining or tethering, abandonment, unnecessarily denying food or water, keeping in a dirty or parasitic condition, or failing to provide veterinary assistance.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] There is also a general provision prohibiting wanton, unreasonable, or negligible commission or omission of acts resulting in unnecessary suffering.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries for 2013/14 to 2016/17 mentions updating animal protection legislation.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The NSPCA is the largest and oldest animal welfare organization in South Africa that enforces 90% of all animal cruelty cases in the country by means of enforcing the Animals Protection Act.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Criminal Code of South Sudan has laws against the maltreatment of animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In Argentina, National Law 14346 sanctions from 15 days to one year in prison for those who mistreat or inflict acts of cruelty on animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Tourism is one of the main economic activities in Argentina, and animals are often used as part of the attractions offered to visitors.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Several of these practices have raised concerns regarding animal welfare.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Horses have historically been part of Argentine culture and identity.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In some tourist cities, horse-drawn carriages (*carruajes*) are still used as attractions.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] NGOs such as *Caballos en Libertad* in Buenos Aires and *Fundación Sin Estribos* in Córdoba rescue mistreated horses.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Reports of overwork, inadequate care, and abuse have prompted municipal authorities to propose restrictions and reforms.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] At Iguazú National Park, the interaction between tourists and coatis has been described as problematic.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Visitors often feed coatis with human food, which alters their diet, generates dependency, and exposes them to health issues.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Close interactions, such as touching or taking photographs at very short distance, have also been reported to cause aggressive behavior and accidents.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Park authorities and researchers warn that such practices disrupt the animals' natural behavior and may increase human-wildlife conflicts.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Brazil is a high-volume animal producer, slaughtering around 30.8 land-based animals per person per year, compared to a global average of 10.1.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The country's dependency on farmed animals is relatively high, with around 8 farmed animals per person, double the global average of 4.1.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] A 1998 law prohibits the abuse of domestic and wild animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] It imposes more serious penalties for cruelty than the 1934 decree, with a sentence of 3 months to a year plus a fine, with the penalty increased by one-sixth to one-third of the animal is killed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In Canada, it is an offense under the Criminal Code to intentionally cause unnecessary pain, suffering, or injury to an animal.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Poisoning animals is specifically prohibited.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] It is also an offense to threaten to harm an animal belonging to someone else.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Most provinces and territories also have animal protection legislation.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] However, it is not explicitly illegal in Canadian law to kill a dog or cat for consumption.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Animal Legal Defense Fund releases an annual report ranking the animal protection laws of every province and territory based on their relative strength and general comprehensiveness.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In 2014, the strongest four jurisdictions were Manitoba, British Columbia, Ontario, and Nova Scotia.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The weakest four were Saskatchewan, Northwest Territories, Quebec, and Nunavut.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Law 20380 established sanctions including fines, from 2 to 30 Mensual Tributary Units, and prison, from 541 days to 3 years, for those involved in acts of animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Also, it facilitates animal care through school education and establishes a Bioethics Committee to define policies related to experiments with animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In Colombia, there is little control over cruel behaviors against animals, and the government has proposed that bullfighting be declared a "Cultural Heritage".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Other activities like cockfighting are given the same legal treatment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In 2017, after many years of legal wrangling, Costa Rica passed their Animal Welfare Law.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] It includes prison sentences of three months to one year for harming or killing a domesticated animal or for conducting animal fights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] There are monetary fines for those who mistreat, neglect or abandon animals, for breeding or training animals for fighting, or for violating regulations on animal experimentation.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The law does not cover agricultural practices, aquaculture, zootechnical or veterinary activities, killing of animals for consumption, for sanitary or scientific reasons, or reproductive control.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Wild animals are covered under the Wild Life Act.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The bill had stalled its motion through the legislature until an injured toucan was found which had lost the top half of its beak.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] News and images of the injured bird, now named Grecia, raised enough contributions to create a 3D printed prosthesis for her, and helped spur the bill's progress.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The current policy of Mexico, in civil law, condemns physical harm to animals as property damage to the owners of the abused animal, considering the animals as owned property.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In criminal law, the situation is different.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In December 2012, the Legislative Assembly of the Federal District reformed the existing Penal Code of Mexico City, establishing abuse and cruelty to animals as criminal offenses, provided the animals are not deemed to be plagues or pests.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Abandoned animals are not considered to be plagues.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] A subsequent reform was entered into force on 31 January 2013, by a decree published in the Official Gazette of the Federal District.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The law provides penalties of six months to two years imprisonment, and a fine of 50 to 100 days at minimum wage, to persons who cause obvious injury to an animal, and the penalty is increased by one-half of those injuries endanger its life.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The penalty rises to two to four years of prison, and a fine of 200 to 400 days at minimum wage, if the person intentionally causes the death of an animal.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] This law is considered to extend throughout the rest of the 31 constituent states of the country.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In addition, The Law of Animal Protection of the Federal District is wide-ranging, based on banning "unnecessary suffering".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The primary federal law relating to animal care and conditions in the US is the Animal Welfare Act of 1966, amended in 1970, 1976, 1985, 1990, 2002, and 2007.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] It is the only Federal law in the United States that regulates the treatment of animals in research, exhibition, transport, and by dealers.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Other laws, policies, and guidelines may include additional species coverage or specifications for animal care and use, but all refer to the Animal Welfare Act as the minimum acceptable standard.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Animal Legal Defense Fund releases an annual report ranking the animal protection laws of every state based on their relative strength and general comprehensiveness.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In a 2013's report, the top five states for their strong anti-cruelty laws were Illinois, Maine, Michigan, Oregon, and California.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The five states with the weakest animal cruelty laws in 2013 were Kentucky, Iowa, South Dakota, New Mexico, and Wyoming.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In Massachusetts and New York, agents of humane societies and associations may be appointed as special officers to enforce statutes outlawing animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In the United States, ear cropping, tail docking, rodeo sports, and other acts are legal and sometimes condoned.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Penalties for cruelty can be minimal if pursued.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Currently, 46 of the 50 states have enacted felony penalties for certain forms of animal abuse.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] However, in most jurisdictions, animal cruelty is most commonly charged as a misdemeanor offense.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In one recent California case, a felony conviction for animal cruelty could theoretically net a 25-year to a life sentence due to their three-strikes law, which increases sentences based on prior felony convictions.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In 2003, West Hollywood, California, passed an ordinance banning declawing of house cats.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In 2007, Norfolk, Virginia passed legislation only allowing the procedure for medical reasons.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] However, most jurisdictions allow the procedure.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In April 2013, Texas Federal Court Judge Sim Lake ruled that the Animal Crush Video Prohibition Act of 2010, which criminalized the recording, sale, and transport of videos depicting animal cruelty as obscenity, violates the First Amendment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Judge Lake noted that obscenity tests require an explicitly sexual depiction, which the criminalized videos lack.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] This follows the precedent set by *United States v.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Stevens*, which additionally held that restrictions on the possession of animal cruelty videos were unconstitutional.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] President Donald Trump signed the Preventing Animal Cruelty and Torture Act, making certain intentional acts of cruelty to animals federal crimes carrying penalties of up to seven years in prison.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Act expanded upon the 2010 Animal Crush Video Prohibition Act signed by President Barack Obama that banned the creation and distribution of videos that showed animals being crushed, burned, drowned, suffocated, impaled, or subjected to other forms of torture.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The underlying acts, which were not included in the 2010 bill, are part of the PACT Act and are now federal offenses.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The bill was unanimously passed in both the House and Senate.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Several states have enacted or considered laws in support of humane farming.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Venezuela published a "Law for Protection of Domestic Fauna free and in captivity" in 2010, defining responsibilities and sanctions regarding animal care and ownership.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Animal cruelty acts are fined, but are not a cause for imprisonment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The law also forbids the possession, breeding, and reproduction of pit bull dogs, among similar breeds that are alleged to be aggressive and dangerous.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] It elicited reactions from dog owners, who said that aggressiveness in dogs is determined more by treatment by the owner than by the breed itself.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Israel banned the sale of fur to the fashion industry in June 2021.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] As of the year 2006, there were no laws in China governing acts of cruelty to animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] There are no government-supported charitable organizations like the RSPCA, which monitors the cases of animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] All kinds of animal abuses, such as to fish, tigers, and bears, are to be reported to law enforcement and animal welfare.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In the absence of a unified law against animal mistreatment, the World Animal Protection notes that some legislation protecting the welfare of animals exists in certain contexts, especially ones used in research and zoos.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In September 2009, legislation was drafted to address deliberate cruelty to animals in China.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] If passed, the legislation would offer some protection to pets, captive wildlife, and animals used in laboratories, as well as regulate how farm animals are raised, transported, and slaughtered.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In 2008, the People's Republic of China was in the process of making changes to its stray-dog population laws in the capital city, Beijing.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Zheng Gang who is the director of the Internal and Judicial Committee which comes under the Beijing Municipal People's Congress (BMPC), supported the draft of the Beijing Municipal Regulation on Dogs from the local government.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The law would replace the Beijing Municipal Regulation on Dog Ownership, introduced in 1989.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The extant regulation talked of "strictly" limiting dog ownership and controlling the number of dogs in the city.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] As of 2010, Hong Kong has supplemented or replaced the laws against cruelty with a positive approach using laws that specify how animals should be treated.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The government department primarily responsible for animal welfare in Hong Kong is the Agriculture, Fisheries, and Conservation Department (AFCD).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] As of 2006, Hong Kong has a law titled "Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Ordinance", with maximum of 3-year imprisonment and fines of HKD$200,000.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Act (PCA), 1960 was amended in the year 1982, criminalizes cruelty to animals, though exceptions are made for the treatment of animals used for food and scientific experiments.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The maximum penalty under the Act is Rs.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] 500 (under $10) and upto three months imprisonment for repeat offense, which is continued to be used despite being criticized for low penalty amount that has not been revised for over two decades.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Animal cruelty that do not fall under this are litigated under other parts of legislation, that either generalize to animals or are restrictions on the use of draught animals or performing animals, animal transport, breeding, slaughter, or experimentation.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Many organizations, including ones such as the local SPCA, PF, A, and Fosterdopt are actively involved in assisting the general population in reporting cruelty cases to the police and helping bring the perpetrator to justice.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] A series of amendments of the PCA, proposed in 2011-2022, to increase penalty of offense and impose stricter legislature have not passed through the parliament as of February 2026.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Iranian government sponsored a law banning pets, breeding, selling, walking and keeping in the cities also including Najis animals/birds.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Animals lives and wellbeing are to some limited extent protected under Islamic criminal code and feqh.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Separate national and local ordinances exist about ensuring the health and safety of animals handled by pet shops and other businesses.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Animal experiments are regulated by the 2000 Law for the Humane Treatment and Management of Animals, which was amended in 2006.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] This law requires those using animals to follow the principles outlined in the 3Rs, which are listed as replacement, reduction, and refinement, to use as few animals as possible, and cause minimal distress and suffering.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Regulation is at a local level based on national guidelines, but there are no governmental inspections of institutions and no reporting requirement for the numbers of animals used.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Cruelty towards animals protected under the Animal Welfare Act (2015) is punishable by a fine of 20–100,000 ringgit and/or imprisonment of up to three years.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Cruelty towards animals protected under the Wildlife Conservation Act (2010) is punishable by a fine of 5–50,000 ringgit and/or up to one-year imprisonment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Under the AA, a person commits an offense of animal cruelty if they "cruelly beats, kicks, ill-treats, overrides, overdrives, overloads, tortures, infuriates or terrifies any animal.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Veterinarian Lana Dunn and several Saudi nationals report that there are no laws to protect animals from cruelty since the term is not well-defined within the Saudi legal system.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] They point to a lack of a governing body to supervise conditions for animals, particularly in pet stores and in the exotic animal trade with East Africa.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] South Korea's animal welfare laws are weak by international standards.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Taiwanese Animal Protection Act was passed in 1998, imposing fines of up to NT$250,000 for cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Criminal penalties for animal cruelty were enacted in 2009, including a maximum of one-year imprisonment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Thailand introduced its first animal welfare law in 2014.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The *Cruelty Prevention and Welfare of Animal Act, B.E.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The European Union Council Directive 1999/74/EC is a directive passed by the European Union on the minimum standards for keeping egg laying hens which effectively bans conventional battery cages.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The directive passed in 1999, banned conventional battery cages in the EU from 1 January 2012 after a 13-year phase-out.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] It is also illegal in many parts of Europe to declaw a cat.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In France, cruelty to animals is punishable by imprisonment of two years and a financial penalty (€30,000).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In Germany, killing animals or causing significant pain (or prolonged or repeated pain) to them is punishable by imprisonment of up to three years or a financial penalty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] If the animal is of foreign origin, the act may also be punishable as criminal damage.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Acts of cruelty against animals can be punished with imprisonment, for a minimum of three months up to a maximum of three years, and with a fine ranging from a minimum of 3,000 Euros to a maximum of 160,000 Euros, as for the law n°189/2004.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Animal Health and Welfare Act 2013 came into force in 2014, improving animal protection.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The maximum penalty is up to €250,000 and up to five years in prison.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Sentences of up to three years have been imposed in several cases.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Since 1 October 2014, violence against animals has been a crime in Portugal.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Legislation published in the *Diário da República* on 29 August criminalizes the mistreatment of animals and indicates that "those who, without reasonable cause, inflict pain, suffering, or any other hardship to a companion animal abuse" are to be subject to imprisonment of up to one year.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] If such acts result in the "death of the animal", the "deprivation of an important organ or member", or "serious and permanent impairment of its capacity of locomotion", those responsible will be punished by imprisonment up to two years.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] As for pets, the new law provides that "whoever, having the duty to store, monitor or pet watch, abandons them, thereby putting in danger their food and the provision of care owed" faces up to six months imprisonment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In Sweden some forms of cruelty to animals is punishable by a financial penalty and prison for up to two years.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The owner will lose the right to own animals and the animals will be removed from the owner.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Swiss animal protection laws are among the strictest in the world, comprehensively regulating the treatment of animals including the size of rabbit cages, and the amount of exercise that must be provided to dogs.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In the canton of Zurich an animal lawyer, Antoine Goetschel, is employed by the canton government to represent the interests of animals in animal cruelty cases.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Under Turkey's Animal Protection Law No.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] 5199, cruelty to animals is considered a criminal offense, punishable by up to four years in prison.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In July 2021, Turkey banned the opening of circuses which use animals, and dolphinariums.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Existing facilities will cease operations in ten years.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] HAYTAP, the Animal Rights Federation in Turkey, used to believe that the previous law did not contain a strong enough punishment for animal abusers.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In 2024, a cruelty to animals case caused widespread outrage in social media in Turkey.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Eros, a cat kept in a housing complex in Küçükçekmece, Istanbul, was tortured to death by İbrahim Keloğlan on 1 January in the early morning.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The moments when Keloğlan tortured Eros to death were recorded by the security cameras of the site.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Keloğlan was released with a good behavior discount at the first hearing of the case held on 8 February at the Küçükçekmece 16th Criminal Court of First Instance.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] A campaign was launched on social media against Keloğlan, who was given a good behavior discount, saying "Let İbrahim Keloğlan be arrested".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] A similar incident also occurred in 2025.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Burak Alan, who came to a Başakşehir housing complex for renovations, tortured and killed a 6-year-old cat whose name was Cezve that approached him inside the building.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The moment Alan tortured the cat was recorded second by second by the building's security camera.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Justice Minister Yılmaz Tunç stated, "Following images circulating on social media of a cat being brutally kicked to death in Başakşehir, Istanbul, the Küçükçekmece Chief Public Prosecutor's Office immediately launched a judicial investigation under Law No.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The suspect has been apprehended and detained, and legal proceedings regarding the incident are being meticulously pursued.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] These images of violence are unacceptable, neither in good conscience nor legally.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Violence against animals will never go unpunished." Burak Alan, who was referred to Küçükçekmece Courthouse, was arrested under the "Animal Protection Law" and sent to prison.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Burak Alan was sentenced to 3 years and 8 months in prison for "deliberately killing a pet.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In the United Kingdom, cruelty to animals is a criminal offense for which one may be jailed for up to 6 months.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] On 18 August 1911, the House of Commons introduced the Protection of Animals Act 1911 (c.27) following lobbying by the Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (RSPCA).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The maximum punishment was six months of hard labour with a fine of 25 pounds.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In the Metropolitan Police Act 1839 "fighting or baiting Lions, Bears, Badgers, Cocks, Dogs, or other Animals" was prohibited in London, with a penalty of up to one-month imprisonment, with possible hard labor, or up to five pounds.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The law laid numerous restrictions on how, when, and where animals could be driven, wagons unloaded, etc.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] It also prohibited owners from letting mad dogs run loose and gave police the right to destroy any dog suspected of being rabid or any dog bitten by a suspected rabid dog.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The same law prohibited the use of dogs for drawing carts.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Up until then, dogs were used for delivering milk, bread, fish, meat, fruit, vegetables, animal food (the cat's-meat man), and other items for sale and for collecting refuse (the rag-and-bone man).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] As Nigel Rothfels notes the prohibition against dogs pulling carts in or near London caused most of the dogs to be killed by their owners as they went from being contributors to the family income to unaffordable expenses.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Cart dogs were replaced by people with handcarts.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] About 150,000 dogs were killed or abandoned.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Protection of Animals Act 1911 extended the ban on draft dogs to the rest of the kingdom.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] As many as 600,000 dogs were killed or abandoned.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Protection of Animals Act 1911 has since been largely superseded by the Animal Welfare Act 2006, which also superseded and consolidated more than 20 other pieces of legislation, including the Protection of Animals Act 1934 and the Abandonment of Animals Act 1960.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Act introduced a new welfare offense, which means that animal owners have a positive duty of care, and outlaws neglect to provide for their animals' basic needs, such as access to adequate nutrition and veterinary care.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Under the Criminal Damage Act 1971, domestic animals can be classed as property that is capable of being "damaged or destroyed".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] A charge of criminal damage may be appropriate for the injury or death of an animal owned by someone other than the defendant, and prosecution under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 may also be appropriate.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] In Australia, all states and territories have enacted legislation governing animal welfare.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Welfare laws have been criticized as not adequately protecting animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] Whilst police maintain an overall jurisdiction in the prosecution of criminal matters, in many states officers of the RSPCA and other animal welfare charities are accorded authority to investigate and prosecute animal cruelty offenses.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-cruelty-p04] The Animal Welfare Act 1999 protects animals from maltreatment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Broadly speaking, and particularly in popular discourse, the term "animal rights" is often used synonymously with "animal protection" or "animal liberation".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] More narrowly, "animal rights" refers to the idea that many animals have fundamental rights to be treated with respect as individuals—rights to life, liberty, and freedom from torture—that may not be overridden by considerations of aggregate welfare.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Like human rights, animal rights center on the notion of freedom.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Many animal rights advocates oppose assigning moral value and fundamental protections on the basis of species membership alone.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] They consider this idea, known as speciesism, a prejudice as irrational as any other, and hold that animals should not be considered property or used as food, clothing, entertainment, or beasts of burden merely because they are not human.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Cultural traditions such as Jainism, Taoism, Hinduism, Buddhism, Shinto, and animism also espouse varying forms of animal rights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In parallel to the debate about moral rights, North American law schools now often teach animal law, and several legal scholars, such as Steven M.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Francione, support extending basic legal rights and personhood to nonhuman animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The animals most often considered in arguments for personhood are apes, especially great apes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Some animal-rights academics support this because it would break the species barrier, but others oppose it because it predicates moral value on mental complexity rather than sentience alone.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] As of November 2019, 29 countries had enacted bans on hominoid experimentation; Argentina granted captive orangutans basic human rights in 2014.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Outside of primates, animal-rights discussions most often address the status of mammals (compare charismatic megafauna).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Other animals (considered less sentient) have gained less attention—insects relatively little (outside Jainism) and animal-like bacteria hardly any.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The vast majority of animals have no legally recognised rights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Critics of animal rights argue that nonhuman animals are unable to enter into a social contract, and thus cannot have rights, a view summarised by the philosopher Roger Scruton, who writes that only humans have duties, and therefore only humans have rights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Certain forms of animal-rights activism, such as the destruction of fur farms and of animal laboratories by the Animal Liberation Front, have attracted criticism, including from within the animal-rights movement itself, and prompted the U.S.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Congress to enact laws, including the Animal Enterprise Terrorism Act, allowing the prosecution of this sort of activity as terrorism.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Hemachandra, a 12th-century Jain scholar and monk, achieved a significant political victory for vegetarianism in Indian history.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] He converted King Kumarapala of the Chaulukya dynasty (who ruled present-day Gujarat and surrounding areas) to Jainism.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Under Hemachandra's guidance, Kumarapala issued sweeping imperial edicts (*amari-ghoshana*) that banned the slaughter of animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] This alliance is historically responsible for cementing Gujarat as the geographic epicenter of strict vegetarian cuisine in India.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In the 16th century, the Jain monk Hiravijaya Suri was invited to the court of the Mughal Emperor Akbar.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Through philosophical discussions about nonviolence, the monk persuaded Akbar to issue imperial edicts (*farmans*) that enforced animal welfare across the empire.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] These edicts banned the slaughter of animals for several months of the year, prohibited fishing in specific sacred lakes, and mandated the release of thousands of caged birds.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] This represents one of the earliest recorded instances of state-enforced animal welfare and dietary restrictions at the imperial level in Indian history.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Jain communities established large-scale systems for animal welfare long ago.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Jain merchants funded the creation of *panjrapoles*—specialized animal shelters and hospitals designed to care for sick, old, or rescued livestock and birds.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The motivation for these shelters was not ethical philosophy, but the core Jain religious belief that committing violence against any living creature directly harms a person's soul and spiritual purity.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Serious discussion about animal rights began in 18th- and 19th-century Europe, but respect for animals can be found in most cultures and traditions, including Hinduism, Buddhism, Jainism, and some African and Indigenous cultures.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In the Western world, Aristotle viewed animals as lacking reason and existing for human use, though other ancient philosophers believed animals deserved gentle treatment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Major religious traditions, chiefly Indian or Dharmic religions, opposed animal cruelty.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] While scholars like Descartes saw animals as unconscious automata, and Kant denied direct duties to animals, Jeremy Bentham emphasized their capacity to suffer.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The publications of Charles Darwin eventually eroded the Cartesian view of animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Darwin noted the mental and emotional continuity between humans and animals, suggesting the possibility of animal suffering.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The anti-vivisection movement emerged in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, driven significantly by women.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] From the 1970s onward, growing scholarly and activist interest in animal treatment has aimed to raise awareness and reform laws to improve animal rights and human–animal relationships.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] These can be illustrated by the behavior of exploited animals (as in farming, labor, scientific laboratories), particularly their resistance to manipulation and confinement, including attempts to escape when opportunities arise.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] For some the basis of animal rights is in religion or animal worship (or in general nature worship), with some religions banning killing any animal.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In other religions animals are considered unclean.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Hindu and Buddhist societies abandoned animal sacrifice and embraced vegetarianism from the 3rd century BCE.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] One of the most important sanctions of the Jain, Hindu, and Buddhist faiths is the concept of ahimsa, or refraining from the destruction of life.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] According to Buddhism, humans do not deserve preferential treatment over other living beings.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The Dharmic interpretation of this doctrine prohibits the killing of any living being.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] These Indian religions' dharmic beliefs are reflected in the ancient Indian works of the Tolkāppiyam and Tirukkural, which contain passages that extend the idea of nonviolence to all living beings.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The historical codification of Jain vegetarianism as a universal mandate for the lay community is sociologically anchored in the narrative of Neminatha, the 22nd *tirthankara*.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] According to Jain tradition, Prince Neminatha abandoned his royal wedding in Junagadh upon hearing the cries of captive animals slated to be slaughtered for the wedding feast.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] His renunciation is said to be followed by his meditation at Mount Girnar.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] His refusal to predicate personal celebration upon animal slaughter served as a defining cultural catalyst.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Scholars identify this event as the foundational charter myth that shifted vegetarianism from an isolated ascetic exercise in self-denial into a universal ethical baseline regarding animal welfare for the entire Jain community.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In Islam, animal rights were recognized early by the Sharia.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] This recognition is based on both the Qur'an and the Hadith.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The Qur'an contains many references to animals, detailing that they have souls, form communities, communicate with God, and worship Him in their own way.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Muhammad forbade his followers to harm any animal and asked them to respect animals' rights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Nevertheless, Islam does allow eating of certain species of animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] According to Christianity, all animals, from the smallest to the largest, are cared for and loved.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] According to the Bible, "All these animals waited for the Lord, that the Lord might give them food at the hour.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The two main philosophical approaches to animal ethics are utilitarian and rights-based.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The former is exemplified by Peter Singer, and the latter by Tom Regan and Gary Francione.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Deontologists argue that there are acts we should never perform, even if failing to do so entails a worse outcome.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] There are a number of positions that can be defended from a consequentalist or deontologist perspective, including the capabilities approach, represented by Martha Nussbaum, and the egalitarian approach, which has been examined by Ingmar Persson and Peter Vallentyne.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The capabilities approach focuses on what individuals require to fulfill their capabilities: Nussbaum (2006) argues that animals need a right to life, some control over their environment, company, play, and physical health.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Clark, Mary Midgley, and Bernard Rollin also discuss animal rights in terms of animals being permitted to lead a life appropriate for their kind.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Egalitarianism favors an equal distribution of happiness among all individuals, which makes the interests of the worse off more important than those of the better off.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Another approach, virtue ethics, holds that in considering how to act we should consider the character of the actor, and what kind of moral agents we should be.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Rosalind Hursthouse has suggested an approach to animal rights based on virtue ethics.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Mark Rowlands has proposed a contractarian approach.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Nussbaum (2004) writes that utilitarianism, starting with Jeremy Bentham and John Stuart Mill, has contributed more to the recognition of the moral status of animals than any other ethical theory.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The utilitarian philosopher most associated with animal rights is Peter Singer, professor of bioethics at Princeton University.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Singer is not a rights theorist, but uses the language of rights to discuss how we ought to treat individuals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Until 2014, he was a preference utilitarian, meaning that he judged the rightness of an act by the extent to which it satisfies the preferences (interests) of those affected.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] His position is that there is no reason not to give equal consideration to the interests of human and nonhumans, though his principle of equality does not require identical treatment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] A mouse and a man both have an interest in not being kicked, and there are no moral or logical grounds for failing to accord those interests equal weight.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Interests are predicated on the ability to suffer, nothing more, and once it is established that a being has interests, those interests must be given equal consideration.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Singer argues that equality of consideration is a prescription, not an assertion of fact: if the equality of the sexes were based only on the idea that men and women were equally intelligent, we would have to abandon the practice of equal consideration if this were later found to be false.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] But the moral idea of equality does not depend on matters of fact such as intelligence, physical strength, or moral capacity.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Equality therefore cannot be grounded on the outcome of scientific investigations into the intelligence of nonhumans.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] All that matters is whether they can suffer.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] People now accept that animals suffer and feel pain, but it was not always so.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Bernard Rollin, professor of philosophy, animal sciences, and biomedical sciences at Colorado State University, writes that Descartes's influence continued to be felt until the 1980s.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Veterinarians trained in the US before 1989 were taught to ignore pain, he writes, and at least one major veterinary hospital in the 1960s did not stock narcotic analgesics for animal pain control.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In his interactions with scientists, he was often asked to "prove" that animals are conscious, and to provide "scientifically acceptable" evidence that they could feel pain.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The ability of animals to suffer, even it may vary in severity, is the basis for Singer's application of equal consideration.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The problem of animal suffering, and animal consciousness in general, arose primarily because it was argued that animals have no language.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Singer writes that, if language were needed to communicate pain, it would often be impossible to know when humans are in pain, though we can observe pain behavior and make a calculated guess based on it.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] He argues that there is no reason to suppose that the pain behavior of nonhumans would have a different meaning from the pain behavior of humans.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Tom Regan, professor emeritus of philosophy at North Carolina State University, argues in *The Case for Animal Rights* (1983) that nonhuman animals are what he calls "subjects-of-a-life", and as such are bearers of rights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] He writes that, because the moral rights of humans are based on their possession of certain cognitive abilities, and because these abilities are also possessed by at least some nonhuman animals, such animals must have the same moral rights as humans.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Although only humans act as moral agents, both marginal-case humans, such as infants, and at least some nonhumans must have the status of "moral patients".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Moral patients are unable to formulate moral principles, and as such are unable to do right or wrong, even though what they do may be beneficial or harmful.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Only moral agents are able to engage in moral action.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Animals for Regan have "intrinsic value" as subjects-of-a-life, and cannot be regarded as a means to an end, a view that places him firmly in the abolitionist camp.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] His theory does not extend to all animals, but only to those that can be regarded as subjects-of-a-life.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Whereas Singer is primarily concerned with improving the treatment of animals and accepts that, in some hypothetical scenarios, individual animals might be used legitimately to further human or nonhuman ends, Regan believes we ought to treat nonhuman animals as we would humans.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] He applies the strict Kantian ideal (which Kant himself applied only to humans) that they ought never to be sacrificed as a means to an end, and must be treated as ends in themselves.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Gary Francione, professor of law and philosophy at Rutgers Law School in Newark, is a leading abolitionist writer, arguing that animals need only one right, the right not to be owned.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Everything else would follow from that paradigm shift.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] He writes that, although most people would condemn the mistreatment of animals, and in many countries there are laws that seem to reflect those concerns, "in practice the legal system allows any use of animals, however abhorrent." The law only requires that any suffering not be "unnecessary".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In deciding what counts as "unnecessary", an animal's interests are weighed against the interests of human beings, and the latter almost always prevail.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Francione's *Animals, Property, and the Law* (1995) was the first extensive jurisprudential treatment of animal rights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In it, Francione compares the situation of animals to the treatment of slaves in the United States, where legislation existed that appeared to protect them while the courts ignored that the institution of slavery itself rendered the protection unenforceable.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] He offers as an example the United States Animal Welfare Act, which he describes as an example of symbolic legislation, intended to assuage public concern about the treatment of animals, but difficult to implement.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] He argues that a focus on animal welfare, rather than animal rights, may worsen the position of animals by making the public feel comfortable about using them and entrenching the view of them as property.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] His position in 1996 was that there is no animal rights movement in the United States.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Mark Rowlands, professor of philosophy at the University of Florida, has proposed a contractarian approach, based on the original position and the veil of ignorance—a "state of nature" thought experiment that tests intuitions about justice and fairness—in John Rawls's *A Theory of Justice* (1971).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The idea is that, operating behind the veil of ignorance, they will choose a social contract in which there is basic fairness and justice for them no matter the position they occupy.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Rawls did not include species membership as one of the attributes hidden from the decision-makers in the original position.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Rowlands proposes extending the veil of ignorance to include rationality, which he argues is an undeserved property similar to characteristics including race, sex and intelligence.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] American philosopher Timothy Garry has proposed an approach that deems nonhuman animals worthy of *prima facie* rights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In a philosophical context, a *prima facie* (Latin for "on the face of it" or "at first glance") right is one that appears to be applicable at first glance, but upon closer examination may be outweighed by other considerations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In his book *Ethics: A Pluralistic Approach to Moral Theory*, Lawrence Hinman characterizes such rights as "the right is real but leaves open the question of whether it is applicable and overriding in a particular situation".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The idea that nonhuman animals are worthy of *prima facie* rights is to say that, in a sense, animals have rights that can be overridden by many other considerations, especially those conflicting a human's right to life, liberty, property, and the pursuit of happiness.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In sum, Garry suggests that humans have obligations to nonhuman animals; animals do not, and ought not to, have uninfringible rights against humans.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Women have played a central role in animal advocacy since the 19th century.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The anti-vivisection movement in the 19th and early 20th century in England and the United States was largely run by women, including Frances Power Cobbe, Anna Kingsford, Lizzy Lind af Hageby and Caroline Earle White (1833–1916).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Garner writes that 70 per cent of the membership of the Victoria Street Society (one of the anti-vivisection groups founded by Cobbe) were women, as were 70 per cent of the membership of the British RSPCA in 1900.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The modern animal advocacy movement has a similar representation of women.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] They are not invariably in leadership positions: during the March for Animals in Washington, D.C., in 1990—the largest animal rights demonstration held until then in the United States—most of the participants were women, but most of the platform speakers were men.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In the Netherlands, Marianne Thieme and Esther Ouwehand were elected to parliament in 2006 representing the Parliamentary group for Animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Lori Gruen writes that women and animals serve the same symbolic function in a patriarchal society: both are "the used"; the dominated, submissive "Other".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In her works *The Sexual Politics of Meat: A Feminist-Vegetarian Critical Theory* (1990) and *The Pornography of Meat* (2004), Carol J.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Adams focuses in particular on what she argues are the links between the oppression of women and that of non-human animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Some transhumanists argue for animal rights, liberation, and "uplift" of animal consciousness into machines.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Transhumanism also understands animal rights on a gradation or spectrum with other types of sentient rights, including human rights and the rights of conscious artificial intelligences (posthuman rights).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] According to sociologist David Nibert of Wittenberg University, the struggle for animal liberation must happen in tandem with a more generalized struggle against human oppression and exploitation under global capitalism.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] According to sociologist Richard Twine, animals themselves serve as producers and product for human consumption within a global capitalist system.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] He believes that the capitalist system exploits animals as a producer and a product, which he calls the "profoundly speciesist animal-industrial complex".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Many members of Germany's Nazi Party were proponents of vegetarianism and animal rights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Adolf Hitler regarded himself as a vegetarian, and according to a transcript of one of Hitler's Table Talks, he said "the world of the future will be vegetarian." Other radical proponents of animal rights included Hindu writer Savitri Devi, the author of Impeachment of Man.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Today there is a growing ecofascist movement influenced by past rightist commentators that incorporates animal rights into its ideology.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Frey, professor of philosophy at Bowling Green State University, is a preference utilitarian.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In his early work, *Interests and Rights* (1980), Frey disagreed with Singer—who wrote in *Animal Liberation* (1975) that the interests of nonhuman animals must be given equal consideration when judging the consequences of an act—on the grounds that animals have no interests.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Frey argues that interests are dependent on desire, and that no desire can exist without a corresponding belief.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Animals have no beliefs, because a belief state requires the ability to hold a second-order belief—a belief about the belief—which he argues requires language: "If someone were to say, e.g.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Carl Cohen, professor of philosophy at the University of Michigan, argues that rights holders must be able to distinguish between their own interests and what is right.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] "The holders of rights must have the capacity to comprehend rules of duty governing all, including themselves.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In applying such rules, [they] ... must recognize possible conflicts between what is in their own interest and what is just.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Cohen writes that the test for moral judgment "is not a test to be administered to humans one by one", but should be applied to the capacity of members of the species in general.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Judge Richard Posner of the United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit debated the issue of animal rights in 2001 with Peter Singer.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Posner posits that his moral intuition tells him "that human beings prefer their own.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] If a dog threatens a human infant, even if it requires causing more pain to the dog to stop it, than the dog would have caused to the infant, then we favour the child.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Singer challenges this by arguing that formerly unequal rights for gays, women, and certain races were justified using the same set of intuitions.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Posner replies that equality in civil rights did not occur because of ethical arguments, but because facts mounted that there were no morally significant differences between humans based on race, sex, or sexual orientation that would support inequality.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] If and when similar facts emerge about humans and animals, the differences in rights will erode too.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] But facts will drive equality, not ethical arguments that run contrary to instinct, he argues.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Posner calls his approach "soft utilitarianism", in contrast to Singer's "hard utilitarianism".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Roger Scruton, the British philosopher, argued that rights imply obligations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] He accused animal rights advocates of "pre-scientific" anthropomorphism, attributing traits to animals that are, he says, Beatrix Potter-like, where "only man is vile." It is within this fiction that the appeal of animal rights lies, he argued.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The world of animals is non-judgmental, filled with dogs who return our affection almost no matter what we do to them, and cats who pretend to be affectionate when, in fact, they care only about themselves.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] It is, he argued, a fantasy, a world of escape.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Scruton singled out Peter Singer, a prominent Australian philosopher and animal-rights activist, for criticism.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] He wrote that Singer's works, including *Animal Liberation*, "contain little or no philosophical argument.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Tom Regan countered this view of rights by distinguishing moral agents and moral patients.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] According to a 2000 paper by Harold Herzog and Lorna Dorr, previous academic surveys of attitudes toward animal rights tended to have small sample sizes and non-representative groups.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] But a number of factors appear to correlate with people's attitudes about the treatment of animals and animal rights.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] These include gender, age, occupation, religion, and level of education.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] There is also evidence suggesting that experience with pets may be a factor in people's attitudes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] According to some studies, women are more likely to empathize with the cause of animal rights than men.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] A 1996 study suggested that factors that may partially explain this discrepancy include attitudes towards feminism and science, scientific literacy, and the presence of a greater emphasis on "nurturance or compassion" among women.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] A common misconception about animal rights is that its proponents want to grant nonhuman animals the same legal rights as humans, such as the right to vote.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Rather, the idea is that animals should have rights that accord with their interests (for example, cats have no interest in voting, and so should not have the right to vote).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] A 2016 study found that support for animal testing may not be based on cogent philosophical rationales and that more open debate is warranted.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The findings extended previous research, such as a 1992 study that found that 48% of animal rights activists were atheists or agnostic.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] A 2019 *Washington Post* study found that those with favorable attitudes toward animal rights also tend to have favorable views of universal healthcare; reducing discrimination against African Americans, the LGBT community, and undocumented immigrants; and expanding welfare to aid the poor.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Two surveys found that attitudes toward animal rights tactics, such as direct action, are very diverse within the animal rights communities.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Near half (50% and 39% in two surveys) of activists do not support direct action.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] In the U.S., the National Farmers Organization held many public protest slaughters in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] Protesting low prices for meat, farmers killed their animals in front of media representatives.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] The carcasses were wasted and not eaten.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-rights] This effort backfired because it angered people to see animals needlessly and wastefully killed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] An **animal sanctuary** is a facility where animals are brought to live and to be protected for the rest of their lives.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] There are five types of animal sanctuaries determined by the species of the residents: companion animal sanctuaries, wildlife sanctuaries, exotic animal sanctuaries, farmed animal sanctuaries, and cetacean sanctuaries.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Unlike zoos, sanctuaries do not breed animals, exhibit animals for human entertainment, offer visitors the chance to touch animals, or use animals commercially.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Unlike animal shelters, sanctuaries typically do not seek to find new human homes for animals; they provide a safe haven for each animal until their natural death.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] In some cases, an establishment may have characteristics of both a sanctuary and a shelter, however, assisting in rehoming when needed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Animals are not bought, sold, or traded, nor are they used for testing or experimentation.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Additionally, no parts of nor secretions from the animals, such as eggs, wool, or milk, are commodified.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The resident animals are given the opportunity to behave as naturally as possible in a protective environment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] What distinguishes a sanctuary from other institutions is the philosophy that the residents come first.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] In a sanctuary, every action is scrutinized for any trace of human benefit at the expense of non-human residents.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Sanctuaries act on behalf of the animals, and the caregivers work under the notion that all animals in the sanctuary, human and non-human, are of equal importance.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] A legitimate sanctuary avoids activities that place animals in an unduly stressful situations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Thus, they do not sell daily access to the animals, in the manner of zoos.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Most sanctuaries are also not government-funded and are usually nonprofit.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Public help is accepted by sanctuaries in the form of volunteering, monetary contributions, donations of food and materials, spreading the word, and in some cases, adoption.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] One of the most important missions of sanctuaries, beyond caring for the animals, is educating the public.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The ultimate goal of many sanctuaries is to change the way that humans think of, and treat, non-human animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] A wildlife sanctuary provides food, protection, and veterinary care for wild animals that have been rescued from zoos, circuses, and other abusive situations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Some wildlife sanctuaries provide care for multiple species, while others focus on a single species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Sanctuaries that care for more than one species may allow interspecies interaction, but keep predators segregated from prey.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Farmed animal sanctuaries (FAS) provide care, shelter and advocacy of farmed animal species such as chickens, cows, goats, fish, horses, pig, turkeys, and sheep.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The farm sanctuary layout tends to resemble traditional farms however functions differently.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] FAS as a movement began with Gene Baur, the co-founder of Farm Sanctuary, the first official farm sanctuary that opened in 1986.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The daily tasks of a FAS involve the primary guardians, volunteers and at time visitors.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Each day is structured by routines such as feeding, care and health procedures, as well as cleaning and maintenance.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Points of conflict for sanctuaries include human intervention in matters of sterilizing animals and species segregation.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Moreover, effective altruists have critiqued the efficiency of FAS's ability to reduce animal suffering as demonstrated in the "arithmetic of compassion", a utilitarian measure of advocacy that applies mathematical formulas to reduce the most suffering in light of individual lives.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Jon Bockman of Animal Charity Evaluators, states, "expending too many resources on direct rescue results in less money directed toward education and a lower overall impact in helping animals, and all advocates should give consideration to this concern when deciding how best to help animals".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] FAS has, in some ways, evolved to more actions such as re-homing to increase sanctuary capacity and rescuing farmed animals in criminal or domestic cases.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The educational role is a secondary role of FAS.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Investing in transforming visitors' and volunteers' perspectives on animal agriculture is a key component of FAS, enlisting farmed animal residents as "ambassadors" of their species to serve a fundraiser role.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Sue Donaldson and Will Kymlicka have outlined two different types of FAS models.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] FAS can be distinguished by ascribing to either refuge and advocacy model or intentional community model.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Refuge- and advocacy-based models are the most standard.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] These sanctuaries are found in traditional agricultural communities in part because of the physical and legal infrastructure.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Six characteristics of this model include: duty of care, support for species-typical flourishing, recognition of individuality, non-exploitation, non-perpetuation, and awareness and advocacy.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The latter characteristic has launched a series of questions into the effectiveness of the educational component of sanctuaries.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The six characteristics of the intentional community model include: belonging, absence of fixed hierarchical relationships, self-determination, citizenship, dependent agency, and scaffolded choices and reconfigured spaces.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] These characteristics redress some of the critiques of the refuge and advocacy model by grounding sanctuary practices in animal agency and expanding the geographical boundaries of where animals can live.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Expanding the geographies in which farmed animals are found serve as a corrective to forming human-farmed animal friendships.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] An example of the intentional sanctuary model can be found in the Microsanctuary Movement started by Rosemary and Justin Van Kleeck.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The Microsanctuary Movement encourages city-dwellers to rescue farmed animals to expand what species are considered to be companion animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Expanding beyond the traditional role of a safe haven for farmed animals, sanctuaries can also be understood as playing political roles in transforming the political and spatial lives of animal residents and their broader species communities leaning into pioneering a less-speciesist future.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Cetacean sanctuaries are designed for autonomy and well-being, enabling as natural a life as possible in ocean water.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Lifetime of care is provided for these whales, dolphins, or porpoises.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Like other wild animals who have spent much or all of their lives in zoos, cetaceans who have lived in marine parks for most or all of their lives are potentially poor candidates for reintroduction and, therefore, sanctuaries are an alternative to living on display or in entertainment facilities.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Sanctuary site selection, as far as size, water quality, protection from hazards and weather events, and more, introduce unique considerations for finding a location.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The need for cetacean sanctuaries is quickly emerging due to shifting regulations and changes in public attitudes toward cetaceans in captivity.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] With an estimated 3,600 cetaceans in captivity globally, the need for spacious natural ocean environments that provide feeding and care is increasing, as globally marine parks and aquariums move away from whales and dolphins in their facilities.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] A primary criticism of commercial facilities is that animals are expected to perform unnatural behaviors for audiences in spaces that are small and cannot adequately approximate a natural setting.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The first cetacean sanctuary for belugas opened in August 2020 by SEA LIFE Trust, as two belugas "Little Grey" and "Little White" were transported 6,000 miles from an aquarium in China to the first open-water whale sanctuary for belugas in Iceland.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The Whale Sanctuary Project is creating a coastal sanctuary for beluga whales and orcas in Port Hilford, Nova Scotia and plans to welcome their first residents in late 2023, assuming the project gets the required federal and provincial permits.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The National Aquarium in Baltimore, Maryland, is seeking a Caribbean location to create a warm water seaside dolphin sanctuary to become the permanent home for the dolphins currently at their facility.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] And the Archipelagos Institute of Marine Conservation is planning to create the Aegean Marine Life Sanctuary for previously captive dolphins on the island of Lipsi, south of Samos in the eastern Aegean Sea.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Like other animal sanctuaries, cetacean sanctuaries adhere to a set of principles that put the animals first above the needs of the public, researchers, donors or other stakeholders.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] In cetacean sanctuaries, each animal's physical and mental well-being is the priority and the mission is to provide an environment where the cetacean residents can thrive.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Animal sanctuary services include spaying and neutering, hygiene, and physical well-being.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] These services are mainly performed by licensed veterinarians.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Other positions that can be held by people at sanctuaries include specialized animal trainers, groomers, and volunteers.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] When it comes to new residents, they are typically not used to living with a large population of their kind and can be easily overwhelmed or agitated.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Because of this, they can be held for a certain amount of time before being admitted to the general public.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] In this time, veterinarians study the new animal's behavioral and dietary habits and try for a smooth transition into the sanctuary's environment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Also, some species of animals, dogs for example, are social creatures.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] In isolation they get lonely and become depressed.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Animal sanctuaries often accommodate these types of animals by putting them in living quarters where they're in groups or pairs that they fit well with.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Enrichment activities are also available for the residents.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] There are currently over 1500 wildlife sanctuaries in the United States, ranging from elephant rehabilitation (The Elephant Sanctuary, Tennessee) to those caring for farm animals saved from slaughterhouses (Farm Animal Refuge, San Diego, California).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] The largest animal sanctuary in the United States is the Best Friends Animal Sanctuary near Kanab, Utah.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] This sanctuary spans across nearly 4,000 acres and is home to approximately 1,600 animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] While there are many ways to donate and support animal sanctuaries throughout the United States, many sanctuaries have begun bringing awareness to their causes on social media with ranging, but largely significant success.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Many have brought in tens or hundreds of thousands of followers.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] Social media has become an opportunity for sanctuaries to raise awareness of the abuse and cruelty that is present in many animal-based industries and educate the general population on how they can help.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] There are two primary organizations that provide accreditation and support for animal sanctuaries: the Global Federation of Animal Sanctuaries and the American Sanctuary Association.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-sanctuary] In the United States, sanctuaries must also be licensed by the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) and regularly inspected by the Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS) for compliance with the Animal Welfare Act.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-theme-park] An **animal theme park**, also known as a **zoological theme park**, is a combination of an amusement park and a zoo, mainly for entertainment, amusement, and commercial purposes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-theme-park] Many animal theme parks combine classic theme park elements, such as themed entertainment and amusement rides, with classic zoo elements such as live animals confined within enclosures for display.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-theme-park] Many times, live animals are utilized and featured as part of amusement rides and attractions found at animal theme parks.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-theme-park] Two examples of animal theme parks are Disney's Animal Kingdom in Orlando, Florida (580 acres or 2.3 square kilometres) and Busch Gardens Tampa Bay in Tampa, Florida (335 acres or 1.36 square kilometres).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-theme-park] These commercial parks are similar to open-range zoos and safari parks according to size, but different in intention and appearance, containing more entertainment and amusement elements (stage shows, amusement rides, etc.).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-theme-park] In 2010 the practice of keeping animals as trained show performers in theme parks was heavily criticized when a trainer was killed by an orca whale at SeaWorld Orlando in Florida.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-theme-park] Most zoos have a carousel and/or Safari Train, but some zoos have more amusement attractions than that.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] In some countries animal trainer certification bodies exist.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] They do not share consistent goals or requirements; they do not prevent someone from practicing as an animal trainer nor using the title.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Similarly, the United States does not require animal trainers to have any specific certification.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] An animal trainer should consider the natural behaviors of the animal and aim to modify behaviors through a basic system of reward and punishment.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Occurs when an animal's behavior is followed by a stimulus that increases occurrences of the behavior in the future.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Occurs when a behavior is followed by the removal of an aversive stimulus, which causes the occurrences of the behavior to increase in the future.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Occurs when a behavior is followed by the addition of an aversive stimulus.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] This causes a decrease in occurrences of behavior in the future.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Occurs when a behavior is followed by the removal of a stimulus.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] As a result, the occurrences of the behavior decrease in the future.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Behavior analysts emphasize the use of positive reinforcement for increasing desirable behaviors and negative punishment for decreasing undesirable behaviors.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] If punishment is going to be used to decrease an undesirable behavior, the animal must be able to receive positive reinforcement for an alternative behavior.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Reinforcement should be provided according to a predetermined schedule.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] A reinforcer delivery occurs after a set number of responses, but that number varies around an average number.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] A specific number of responses occur before a reinforcer is delivered.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The first response that is emitted after a set but variable amount of time has elapsed is reinforced.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The first response that is emitted after a set time has elapsed is reinforced.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] While continuous reinforcement in a fixed ratio schedule may be necessary for the initial learning stages, a variable ratio schedule is the most effective at maintaining behavior over long periods of time.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] There are various methods animal trainers can use to prompt an animal to respond to a stimulus in a specific way.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] For example, shaping is a process by which successive approximations are rewarded until the desirable response topography is attained.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] An animal trainer can use conditioned reinforcers, like clickers, to bridge the interval between response and positive reinforcement.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Some stimuli that is considered discriminative are signals, targets and cues.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] They can be used to prompt a response from an animal, and can be changed to other stimuli or faded in magnitude.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] In order to delay satiation, reinforcer size should be as small as possible and still be effective for reinforcement.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Also, the timing of the delivery of a reinforcer is crucial.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Initially the interval between response and consequence must be minimal in order for the animal to associate the consequence with the response.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Certain sub-fields of animal training tend to also have certain philosophies and styles.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The degree of trainer protection from the animal and the tasks trained may also vary.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] They can range from entertainment, husbandry (veterinary) behaviors, physical labor or athleticism, habituation to averse stimuli, interaction (or non-interaction) with other humans, or even research (sensory, physiological, cognitive).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Training also may take into consideration the natural social tendencies of the animal species (or even breed), such as predilections for attention span, food-motivation, dominance hierarchies, aggression, or bonding to individuals (conspecifics as well as humans).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Consideration must also be given to practical aspects on the human side such as the ratio of the number of trainers to each animal.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] In some circumstances one animal may have multiple trainers, in others, a trainer might attend simultaneously to many animals in a training session.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Sometimes training is accomplished with a single trainer working individually with a single animal.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] In some species, the number of trainers is irrelevant, yet it can usually achieve the wanted outcome.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Service animals, such as assistance dogs, Capuchin monkeys and miniature horses, are trained to utilize their sensory and social skills to bond with a human and help that person to offset a disability in daily life.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The use of service animals, especially dogs, is an ever-growing field, with a wide range of special adaptations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] In the United States, selected inmates in prisons are used to train service dogs.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] In addition to adding to the short supply of service animals, such programs have produced benefits in improved socialization skills and behavior of inmates.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] For hundreds of years elephants have be trained to work in activities such as logging and in warfare.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Captive elephants can be trained to remember tone, melody, and recognise more than 20 words.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Organizations such as the American Humane Society monitor the use of animals such as those used in the entertainment industry, but they do not monitor their training.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] It is best known for its end credit disclaimer "No Animals Were Harmed" that appears at the end of the credits of films and shows.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The Patsy Award (Picture Animal Top Star of the Year) was originated by the Hollywood office in 1939 after a horse was killed in an on-set accident during the filming of the Tyrone Power film *Jesse James*.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The award now covers both film and television and is separated into four categories: canine, equine, wild and special.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] One animal trainer, Frank Inn, received over 40 Patsy awards.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] While there is a high demand for mammals for film and television, there is also a demand for other animals.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Kutcher has filled this niche for insects.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Basic obedience training tasks for dogs, include walking on a leash, attention, housebreaking, nonaggression, and socialization with humans or other pets.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Dogs are also trained for many other activities, such as dog sports, service dogs, and working dog tasks.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Positive reinforcement for dogs can include primary reinforcers like food or social reinforcers, such as vocal ("good boy") or tactile (stroking) ones.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Positive punishment, if used at all, can be physical, such as pulling on a leash or spanking.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] It may also be vocal, such as saying "bad dog".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Bridges to positive reinforcement, include vocal cues, whistling, and dog whistles, as well as clickers used in clicker training, a method popularized by Karen Pryor.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Negative reinforcement may also be used.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Punishment is also a tool, including withholding of food or physical discipline.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The primary purpose of training horses is to socialize them around humans, teach them to behave in a manner that makes them safe for humans to handle, and, as adults to carry a rider under saddle or to be driven in order to pull a vehicle.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] As prey animals, much effort must be put into training horses to overcome its natural flight or fight instinct and accept handling that would not be natural for a wild animal, such as willingly going into a confined space, or having a predator (a human being) sit on its back.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] As training advances, some horses are prepared for competitive sports, up to the Olympic games, where horses are the only non-human animal athlete that is used at the Olympics.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] All equestrian disciplines from horse racing to draft horse showing require the horse to have specialized training.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Unlike dogs, horses are not motivated as strongly by positive reinforcement rewards as they are motivated by other operant conditioning methods such as the release of pressure as a reward for the correct behavior, called negative reinforcement.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Positive reinforcement techniques such as petting, kind words, rewarding of treats, and clicker training have some benefit, but not to the degree seen in dogs and other predator species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Punishment of horses is effective only to a very limited degree, usually a sharp command or brief physical punishment given within a few seconds of a disobedient act.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Horses do not correlate punishment to a specific behavior unless it occurs immediately.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] They do, however, have a remarkably long memory, and once a task is learned, it will be retained for a very long time.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] For this reason, poor training or allowing bad habits to be learned can be very difficult to remedy at a later date.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Typical training tasks for companion birds include perching, non-aggression, halting feather-picking, controlling excessive vocalizations, socialization with household members and other pets, and socialization with strangers.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The large parrot species frequently have lifespans that exceed that of their human owners, and they are closely bonded to their owners.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Some birds of prey are trained to hunt, an ancient art known as falconry or hawking.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] In China the practice of training cormorants to catch fish has gone on for over 1,200 years.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Training chickens has become a way for trainers of other animals (primarily dogs) to perfect their training technique.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Bob Bailey, formerly of Animal Behavior Enterprises and the IQ Zoo, teaches chicken training seminars where trainers teach poultry to discriminate between shapes, to navigate an obstacle course and to chain behaviors together.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Chicken training is done using operant conditioning, using a clicker and chicken feed for reinforcement.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The first chicken workshops were given by Keller and Marian Breland in 1947–1948 to a group of animal feed salesmen from General Mills, in Minneapolis, Minnesota.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Trained chickens may be confined to a display (Bird Brain) where they play Tic-Tac-Toe against humans for a fee, invented by Bob Bailey and Grant Evans, of Animal Behavior Enterprises.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The moves were chosen by computer and indicated to the chicken by a light invisible to the human player.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] For example, goldfish may swim toward their owners and follow them as they walk through the room, but will not follow anyone else.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The fish may swim up and down, signalling the owner to turn on its aquarium light when it is off, and it will skim the surface until its owner feeds it.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Fish have also been taught to perform more complicated tasks, such as fetching rings, swimming through hoops and tubes, doing the limbo and pushing a miniature soccer ball into a net.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Fish have been taught to distinguish and respond differently to slight differences in human faces displayed on a screen (archerfish) or styles of music (goldfish and koi).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Molluscs, with totally different brain designs, have been taught to distinguish and respond to geometric symbols (cuttlefish and octopus), and have been taught that food behind a clear barrier cannot be eaten (squid).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Animals in public display are sometimes trained for educational, entertainment, management, and husbandry behaviors.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Educational behaviors may include species-typical behaviors under stimulus control such as vocalizations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Entertainment may include display behaviors to show the animal, or simply arbitrary behaviors.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Management includes movement, such as following the trainer, entering crates, or moving from pen to pen, or tank-to-tank through gates.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Husbandry behaviors facilitate veterinary care.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Such voluntary training is important for minimizing the frequency with which zoo collection animals must be anesthetized or physically restrained.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Many marine mammals are trained for entertainment such as bottlenose dolphins, killer whales, belugas, sea lions, and others.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] In a public display situation, the audience's attention is focused on the animal, rather than the trainer; therefore the discriminative stimulus is generally gestural (a hand sign) and sparse in nature.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Unobtrusive dog whistles are used as bridges, and positive reinforcers are either primary (food) or tactile (rub downs), and not vocal.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] However, pinnipeds and mustelids (sea lions, seals, walruses, and otters) can hear in our frequency, so most of the time they will receive vocal reinforcers during shows and performances.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The shows are turned into more of a play production because of this, instead of just a run through of behaviors like cetaceans generally do in their shows.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] Guests can often hear these vocal reinforcers when attending a SeaWorld show.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] During the Clyde and Seamore show, the trainers may say something like: "Good grief, Clyde!" or "Good job, Seamore".
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] The trainers substitute the word "good" in the place of food or rubdowns when teaching a specific behavior to the animals so that the animals no longer need constant feeding as praise for achieving the appropriate behavior.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/animal-training] On an experimental basis, wildlife researchers have employed animal trainers in their interactions with animals in the field.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] AZA is headquartered in Silver Spring, Maryland, and accredits zoos.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] There were 238 accredited zoos and aquariums as of 2025, primarily in the US, with a handful in twelve other countries; additionally, the AZA network contains 14 accredited related facilities.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] In October 1924 the American Association of Zoological Parks and Aquariums was formed as an affiliate of the American Institute of Park Executives.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] In 1966, the American Association of Zoological Parks and Aquariums became a professional branch affiliate of the newly formed National Recreation and Park Association, which absorbed the American Institute of Park Executives.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] In the fall of 1971, the American Association of Zoological Parks and Aquariums membership voted to become an independent association.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] On January 19, 1972, it was chartered as the American Association of Zoological Parks and Aquariums with its executive office located in Wheeling, West Virginia, within the Oglebay Park Good Zoo.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] In 1994, the shorter name American Zoo and Aquarium Association (AZA) was adopted.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] In early 2018, AZA acquired the Wildlife Trafficking Alliance to help grow public awareness about the purchase and sale of illegal wildlife products in the United States.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] The Association of Zoos and Aquariums reported 195 million visitors to its 236 accredited member facilities in 2017.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] The organization is active in nci accreditation, animal care initiatives, education and conservation programs, collaborative research and advocacy.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] AZA serves as an accrediting body for zoos and aquariums and ensures accredited facilities meet higher standards of animal care than required by law.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] Institutions are evaluated every five years in order to ensure standards are met and to maintain accreditation.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] As of March 2025, AZA had 238 accredited facilities in the US and other thirteen countries: Canada, Mexico, Bermuda, The Bahamas, the Dominican Republic, Colombia, Argentina, Spain, Hong Kong, Singapore, South Korea, and United Arab Emirates.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] Approximately 800,000 animals representing 6,000 species are in the care of AZA-accredited facilities, including 1,000 threatened or endangered species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] The association also facilitates both species survival plans and population management plans, which serve to sustainably manage genetically diverse captive populations of various animal species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] AZA holds a conference in September, one of the largest zoo and aquarium professionals' events in the US.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] AZA also manages the citizen science program FrogWatch USA.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] In the United States, any public animal exhibit must be licensed and inspected by the United States Department of Agriculture, United States Environmental Protection Agency, Drug Enforcement Administration, Occupational Safety and Health Administration, and others.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] Depending on the animals they exhibit, the activities of zoos are regulated by laws including the Endangered Species Act, the Animal Welfare Act, the Migratory Bird Treaty Act of 1918 and others.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] Additionally, zoos in North America may choose to pursue accreditation by AZA.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] To achieve accreditation, a zoo must pass an application and inspection process and meet or exceed AZA's standards for animal health and welfare, fundraising, zoo staffing, and involvement in global conservation efforts.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] Inspection is performed by three experts (typically one veterinarian, one expert in animal care, and one expert in zoo management and operations) and then reviewed by a panel of twelve experts before accreditation is awarded.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] This accreditation process is repeated once every five years.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] AZA estimates that there are approximately 2,800 animal exhibits operating under USDA license as of 2019; fewer than 10% are accredited.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] Certification is possible for facilities that hold animals, but are not regularly open to the public.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] AZA's Saving Animals From Extinction (SAFE) program prioritizes collaboration between zoos and aquariums to support highly vulnerable species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] SAFE builds on existing recovery plans to implement strategic conservation and public engagement activities.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] In 2017, AZA member zoos and aquariums invested $15.6 million towards SAFE program species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] There were more than 20 species or taxonomic groups included in the program as of 2019.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] The association has a computerized database called the *Annual Report on Conservation and Science*.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] This helps track AZA research projects worldwide.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] AZA member zoos and aquariums contribute $220 million to conservation projects each year.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] They participate in 115 reintroduction programs, including more than 40 programs for species listed as threatened or endangered under the Endangered Species Act.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] In 2017, member institutions reported participating in field conservation projects benefiting over 860 species in 128 countries.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] AZA zoos and aquariums spent $25 million on research and published 170 books, book chapters, journal articles, conference proceeding papers, posters and theses or dissertations.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] Animal care, health and welfare, followed by species and habitat conservation, describe 68% of the AZA community's research.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] To be a member, a facility must either be accredited or certified.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] Accredited facilities maintain a professional staff and appropriate animal care, and are open to the public on a predictable basis.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/association-of-zoos-and-aquariums] Certified facilities maintain a professional staff and appropriate animal care, but are not open to the public on a predictable basis.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] The **Endangered Wolf Center** is a non-profit wildlife facility in Eureka, Missouri, United States, near St.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] Louis that is dedicated to preserving and reintroducing to the wild critically endangered species of wolves.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] It is certified by the Association of Zoos and Aquariums (AZA).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] Visitors can tour the facility by making a reservation.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] The center was founded in 1971 by renowned naturalist Marlin Perkins and his wife Carol, who saw that wolves around the world were in danger of becoming extinct.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] Its mission is to preserve and protect Mexican wolves, red wolves, and other wild canid species.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] Their purpose and passion is to carefully manage breeding, reintroduction and inspiring education programs.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] Animals born at the facility have been reintroduced to North Carolina (red wolves) and Arizona and New Mexico (Mexican wolves).
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] The center's research focuses on reproductive, behavioral, and nutritional needs for the species housed there.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] The Endangered Wolf Center is a founding member of the AZA's Mexican Wolf and Red Wolf Species Survival Plans.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] As of August 2016, the center had six species of endangered canids: Mexican wolves, red wolves, maned wolves, African painted dogs, fennec foxes, and swift foxes.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] It had more than 20 Mexican gray wolves, more than any other managed breeding facility.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] (Only 97 Mexican wolves were known to exist in the wild as of 2015.) The center serves as the cornerstone of the U.S.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] Fish and Wildlife Service's program to preserve Mexican wolves and reintroduce them to the wild.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] The center offers daytime tours and evening wolf howls.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] The Endangered Wolf Center is an independent 501(c)(3) non-profit and receives no federal or state support.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] Its programs are supported solely by members, donors and visitors.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] The center is on the grounds of Washington University in St.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] It is located off Interstate 44, 7 miles (11 km) west of Interstate 270 and about 20 miles (32 km) southwest of St.
[src:endangered-wolf-center/endangered-wolf-center] The Endangered Wolf Center was originally named the Wild Canid Survival and Research Center.
